01:49.611 --> 01:52.926
- You know the cholera?
- Yes, Mother.

01:53.030 --> 01:56.135
You've seen the signs on the houses
where the coloureds live?

01:56.240 --> 01:57.932
Yes, Mother.

01:58.036 --> 02:00.944
- You know the typhus?
- I do, Mother.

02:04.492 --> 02:07.233
You know what they can do to you?

02:07.337 --> 02:09.699
Yes, Mother.

02:12.708 --> 02:16.108
You are not safe.

02:22.176 --> 02:25.789
You may be directing this movie, Howard,
but what you're asking, we can't do it.

02:25.893 --> 02:28.668
Don't tell me I can't do it.
Don't tell me it can't be done.

02:28.772 --> 02:30.880
The gyro forces are too much here.

02:30.985 --> 02:32.655
You send these planes into simultaneous...

02:32.759 --> 02:36.465
It's the goddamn climax of the picture,
Frank, all right? You make it work.

02:36.569 --> 02:38.849
Look, decrease the vertical trajectory,
if you have to.

02:38.953 --> 02:41.723
A LeRhone rotary won't stall at 60 degrees,
I've done it.

02:41.827 --> 02:45.599
Howard, we're still short two cameras.
We need to cut that sequence down...

02:45.704 --> 02:48.087
We're not cutting anything, all right.
I'll get those extra cameras.

02:48.191 --> 02:48.984
Set up for rehearsals in five.

02:49.088 --> 02:51.820
Mr Hughes, I'm Noah Dietrich.
Your office said I might find you here.

02:51.924 --> 02:56.739
Dietrich. You're a man on the come. I read
your rÃ©sumÃ© and talked to your references.

02:56.843 --> 02:58.489
You know what I'm looking for?

02:58.594 --> 03:01.663
As I understand it, you're looking for
a second in command at Hughes Tools.

03:01.768 --> 03:04.579
Someone to help oversee
the financial aspects of the business.

03:04.683 --> 03:07.457
Yeah. I'm looking for somebody
to run it and do a damn good job.

03:07.561 --> 03:09.835
Look, there's really one thing
you've got to know.

03:09.939 --> 03:12.962
My folks, they're gone now,
so it's my money.

03:13.066 --> 03:15.302
Now, what I choose to do with
that money may seem crazy

03:15.406 --> 03:18.117
to those sons of bitches in Houston -
and I'm sure as hell it does -

03:18.222 --> 03:20.512
but it all makes good sense to me.
You got that?

03:20.617 --> 03:22.512
- Got it.
- Good.

03:22.617 --> 03:25.808
Now, you made, what,
$5,200 a year on your last job?

03:25.913 --> 03:28.270
I'll pay you 10,000.

03:28.374 --> 03:31.443
- Guess I'll be working twice as hard.
- You'll be working four times as hard.

03:31.547 --> 03:35.110
I just got you at half-price, Mr Dietrich.
Welcome aboard.

03:35.215 --> 03:37.053
You're my voice now.
Make 'em understand that.

03:37.157 --> 03:39.743
Look, some of those fine folks down there
still call me "Junior".

03:39.847 --> 03:42.992
- You tell them it's "Mr Hughes" now.
- You bet.

03:43.096 --> 03:46.747
- So, when do we go to Houston?
- We don't. Cholera epidemic in 1913.

03:46.851 --> 03:49.624
2,000 dead. Whole place is
nothing but pestilential swamp.

03:49.728 --> 03:54.045
Typhus, malaria, cholera, yellow fever -
you name it, they got it.

03:54.149 --> 03:56.545
You see that, Mr Dietrich?

03:56.650 --> 04:00.885
You are looking at the largest
private air force in the entire world.

04:00.989 --> 04:05.360
- What do you think of that, now?
- It's your money.

04:05.905 --> 04:08.505
Start 'em up.

05:34.535 --> 05:36.937
I just saw the rough cut of
the new Tod Browning movie,

05:37.042 --> 05:40.445
<i>London After Midnight.</i>
Lon Chaney is incredible.

05:40.549 --> 05:45.250
It's his best performance in a long time. It's
gonna be a big hit. The cards are great.

05:47.047 --> 05:49.495
Hello, Mr Mayer.

05:49.599 --> 05:52.705
I don't know if you remember me.
My name's Howard Hughes.

05:52.809 --> 05:55.167
I was wondering
if I could have a moment of your time.

05:55.271 --> 05:57.878
Yeah, Howard Hughes.
The airplane picture, right?

05:57.982 --> 05:59.423
- Exactly.
- Yeah, I remember.

05:59.528 --> 06:02.260
- <i>Hell's Angels.</i> You heard of it. Good.
- Yes.

06:02.364 --> 06:04.930
Listen, I was wondering
if I could have a moment of your time.

06:05.034 --> 06:07.510
I need a few cameras.

06:07.614 --> 06:09.308
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

06:09.413 --> 06:11.306
Two, to be exact.

06:11.410 --> 06:13.146
I already bought every camera I could find,

06:13.251 --> 06:15.336
but we're shooting
our big dogfight sequence this week

06:15.440 --> 06:19.104
and I need two more, desperately.
Do you think MGM could help me out?

06:19.209 --> 06:21.819
- With what?
- Cameras.

06:21.923 --> 06:26.874
With the actual cam... We're not usually in
the practice of helping out the competition.

06:28.047 --> 06:31.879
- How many cameras do you have now?
- 24.

06:35.471 --> 06:37.796
Wait a minute.

06:39.350 --> 06:41.003
- You have 24 cameras?
- That's right.

06:41.108 --> 06:44.010
- And you need two more?
- Yeah.

06:44.114 --> 06:47.717
- You don't think you got it with 24?
- No. No, sir.

06:47.822 --> 06:50.475
You know, I think we've got them all...

06:50.580 --> 06:53.055
Don't we have them all?
They're all used.

06:53.159 --> 06:55.519
- All 26 of them.
- I only need two, sir.

06:55.623 --> 06:57.647
- Jesus Christ, sonny...
- Howard.

06:57.751 --> 07:00.606
Howard.
Let me give you a little advice.

07:00.711 --> 07:03.107
- Why don't you take your oil money...
- Drill bits.

07:03.211 --> 07:06.237
Take your drill bit money,
and why don't you put it in the bank?

07:06.341 --> 07:08.848
Because if you continue making the movie
the way that you are,

07:08.952 --> 07:11.371
there isn't gonna be a distributor
who'll want to distribute it.

07:11.476 --> 07:14.078
You're not gonna find anybody
who wants to see the movie,

07:14.182 --> 07:17.168
and you're not gonna have
any more oil money.

07:17.272 --> 07:20.376
So, welcome to Hollywood.

07:20.480 --> 07:23.965
Yeah. Well, I'll be sure
to remember that, Mr Mayer.

07:24.069 --> 07:26.092
- Good luck.
- All right.

07:26.197 --> 07:29.355
He needs 26 to make it work?
He's out of his mind.

07:36.449 --> 07:40.363
I looked down at my pants.
It was a strange situation.

07:41.162 --> 07:42.162
Boss.

07:42.375 --> 07:46.489
Scram, love boat, let's go.
Another soda. You know what I mean.

07:46.593 --> 07:49.492
Milk, please, in the bottle.
With the cap still on.

07:49.596 --> 07:51.224
OK, Howard, what did "His Highness" say?

07:51.328 --> 07:54.592
The son of a bitch won't part with a single
goddamn camera. Can you believe it?

07:54.717 --> 07:57.996
Howard, why don't you try
and make do with what you have?

07:58.100 --> 08:02.418
What I have isn't enough, John.
Not for how I see it. Look.

08:02.522 --> 08:04.131
My name depends on this picture.

08:04.236 --> 08:06.906
If it doesn't work, I'm back to Houston
with my tail between my legs,

08:07.010 --> 08:09.510
making goddamn drill bits
for the rest of my life.

08:09.614 --> 08:11.911
Couldn't you find a way to do it
with the cameras you have?

08:12.015 --> 08:14.997
I mean, jeez, you ought to hear what's
going on with DeMille over at Paramount.

08:15.102 --> 08:17.771
He's shooting this Bible picture, right,
and he's gotta do a crucifixion.

08:17.875 --> 08:19.355
- Johnny.
- He's doing it in Fresno.

08:19.459 --> 08:21.316
- Johnny. Johnny.
- All of a sudden there's...

08:21.421 --> 08:22.900
- Johnny.
- Yeah?

08:23.004 --> 08:25.359
- You're a press agent, are you not?
- Yeah.

08:25.463 --> 08:28.863
And you're supposed to know all the little
ins and outs of Hollywood? Do you?

08:28.968 --> 08:34.243
- Yeah, absolutely.
- Then you leave the big ideas to me.

08:34.347 --> 08:37.256
- Yeah, of course, boss.
- Cigar, cigarettes, Sen-Sen?

08:38.302 --> 08:42.625
Thelma. I thought you were over at
the Brown Derby with Trixie. No, Theresa.

08:42.729 --> 08:45.503
- Margaret, yeah.
- Exactly. What happened to Margaret?

08:45.607 --> 08:48.132
- She lost her shoes?
- Thank God that's settled.

08:48.236 --> 08:51.636
I'm sorry.
Thelma, this is Howard Hughes.

08:51.740 --> 08:56.349
Howard and I were just discussing how he
wants me to pull a camera out of my ass.

08:56.454 --> 09:01.107
- Cigarette?
- Oh, no, thanks. I don't smoke.

09:02.284 --> 09:06.441
Whew. Boy, you are just hitting
on all six cylinders, aren't you?

09:06.545 --> 09:07.945
My God.

09:09.129 --> 09:11.361
Would you do me a favour and just...

09:11.465 --> 09:14.995
Would you just smile for me one time?
Just once?

09:17.049 --> 09:20.290
Whew. Yeah. Yeah.
You see, you got a short upper lip.

09:20.394 --> 09:23.671
Makes for a much nicer smile.

09:27.268 --> 09:31.008
See, I wonder what gives
a beautiful woman like you pleasure.

09:31.112 --> 09:34.845
I mean, say you're just standing there,
right? And I just touch you.

09:34.949 --> 09:38.932
Just like this,
through my fingertips.

09:39.037 --> 09:42.354
Do you...
Do you like that?

09:42.458 --> 09:43.858
Do you?

09:49.081 --> 09:53.072
See, I want to learn what pleases you.

09:53.176 --> 09:56.531
I want to learn everything about you.

09:56.636 --> 10:01.173
Would you let me do that?
Would you give me that job?

10:06.056 --> 10:08.049
I'm off in a half an hour.

10:09.643 --> 10:12.423
- Well, I'm in room...
- 217.

10:12.528 --> 10:13.328
217.

10:16.484 --> 10:19.188
See you there.

10:22.782 --> 10:25.145
Johnny, get on the horn
to Universal and Warner's.

10:25.250 --> 10:28.234
I need two more cameras by Saturday.
Rent 'em if you can.

10:28.338 --> 10:30.988
Steal 'em if you have to.

10:31.092 --> 10:34.747
Abso-tively, boss.
Abso-tively.

10:36.420 --> 10:39.412
Rumours coming from
a lonely airstrip out in Van Nuys.

10:39.516 --> 10:42.914
Sources whisper that young
Texas industrialist Howard Hughes

10:43.018 --> 10:46.750
just won't stop pouring money
into his war epic. And do we mean epic.

10:46.855 --> 10:52.879
137 pilots, 87 airplanes,
35 cameramen, 2,000 extras.

10:52.984 --> 10:56.315
How long will it be before this picture
ends up costing as much as the real war?

10:56.440 --> 10:59.515
Goddamn it.
Why the hell do they look so slow?

10:59.619 --> 11:05.862
This isn't what it was like up there. They
look like a bunch of goddamn models.

11:11.080 --> 11:12.788
Son of a bitch.

11:14.125 --> 11:15.525
Howard?

11:18.129 --> 11:22.074
Without something standing still
behind the planes

11:22.178 --> 11:24.660
we've got no idea of how fast we're moving.

11:24.764 --> 11:28.706
We got no sense of relative motion.

11:28.810 --> 11:31.420
Call over to UCLA.
Get me the best meteorologist they got.

11:31.524 --> 11:34.968
You get him here in an hour, all right?

11:37.273 --> 11:40.014
Hey. You want the good news
or the bad news?

11:40.118 --> 11:41.763
- The bad news, always.
- All right.

11:41.867 --> 11:44.891
We installed the 450 radial
but the struts won't take the vibration.

11:44.995 --> 11:49.228
Minute we fire her up, the struts
start cracking at the attach points.

11:49.333 --> 11:52.273
- Well, what's the good news?
- There isn't any.

11:52.377 --> 11:56.150
Goddamn it, Odie, if the 450's too big,
we just got to figure something else out.

11:56.254 --> 11:59.158
We've done everything.
We've rebuilt her from top to toe.

11:59.262 --> 12:03.032
Now, if we drain the fuel tank, for a couple
of runs, she might make 180mph.

12:03.136 --> 12:04.996
I want minimum 200, all right?

12:05.100 --> 12:07.730
I want a date with Theda Bara,
but that ain't gonna happen either.

12:07.834 --> 12:08.791
Don't be so sure.

12:08.895 --> 12:14.298
So if the struts won't sustain the engine
we need, we got to get rid of the struts.

12:14.403 --> 12:17.311
No, then the top wing falls off.

12:19.190 --> 12:21.176
Then let it.

12:21.280 --> 12:22.280
What?

12:23.699 --> 12:28.356
Who says we need a top wing?
I mean, who says we need anything?

12:30.534 --> 12:33.314
- A monoplane.
- A cantilevered monoplane, right.

12:33.418 --> 12:36.446
I mean, they're doing it in France.
To hell with the top wing and the struts.

12:36.551 --> 12:39.487
- Put in a 550 Wasp engine.
- 100 octane fuel.

12:39.591 --> 12:43.741
- That'd give us a top horsepower of what?
- 700.

12:43.845 --> 12:48.964
We squeeze that to a thousand,
we've got the fastest plane ever built.

12:50.846 --> 12:57.134
You know, I just got to say we've already
spent over $ 200,000 rebuilding this plane.

12:57.728 --> 13:00.387
To hell with it.

13:00.491 --> 13:03.517
Tear it up, Odie.
Go on.

13:06.862 --> 13:07.862
Well.

13:09.452 --> 13:15.035
The cumulonimbus formations
about which you speak...

13:16.372 --> 13:18.525
that look like...

13:18.629 --> 13:22.403
Giant breasts full of milk.
I want clouds, damn it.

13:22.507 --> 13:28.413
Yes, clouds that look like
giant breasts full of milk

13:28.517 --> 13:32.249
cannot exactly be guaranteed
for any particular occasion.

13:32.353 --> 13:34.718
So you might have to...

13:35.599 --> 13:37.199
to wait.

13:39.061 --> 13:41.924
Then we'll wait.

13:42.029 --> 13:46.474
Look, whatever they pay you at UCLA, I'm
doubling it, all right? You work for me now.

13:46.578 --> 13:49.766
Find some clouds.

13:49.870 --> 13:53.438
Find some clouds.
Find me some clouds.

13:53.542 --> 13:56.025
Welcome to <i>Hell's Angels.</i>

13:59.123 --> 14:00.238
Thank you.

14:10.009 --> 14:13.416
We've been to Chatsworth, Santa Cruz,
Encino, San Diego, Riverside,

14:13.521 --> 14:16.337
Van Nuys and Bakersfield.
It has been eight months.

14:16.441 --> 14:20.883
- Where are my goddamn clouds?
- They move, Mr Hughes.

14:20.987 --> 14:24.469
Clouds move.
That's what they do. They move.

14:24.573 --> 14:30.514
See that? It is costing me $5,271 a day
to keep those planes on the ground.

14:30.618 --> 14:34.361
You find me some goddamn clouds.

14:40.831 --> 14:42.631
Nice day.

14:42.800 --> 14:44.861
Yeah, very funny.

14:44.966 --> 14:47.974
Listen, I got a call from Houston.
They're getting real nervous about all this.

14:48.078 --> 14:51.326
- Stop showing them the damn bills, Noah.
- That would be illegal, Howard.

14:51.430 --> 14:53.994
Shit, no.
Maybe it's a little bit naughty.

14:54.099 --> 14:59.294
Hughes Tools is incorporated in Texas.
They have to see the bills.

14:59.399 --> 15:02.799
Incorporate a new division out here,
all right? We'll call it Hughes Aircraft.

15:02.903 --> 15:05.464
Odie, do we need
these rivets on the cowling?

15:05.568 --> 15:07.679
Yeah, or the reverse thrust would rip it off.

15:07.783 --> 15:10.177
They're gonna give me drag.
Do something about that, OK?

15:10.282 --> 15:12.623
- Wind resistance on the rivets?
- Yeah, I want her slippery.

15:12.728 --> 15:15.727
There are serious tax consequences
to incorporating in California.

15:15.831 --> 15:18.899
- Just take care of it, would you?
- Mr Hughes. Mr Hughes.

15:19.004 --> 15:23.279
Oakland.
We have clouds in Oakland.

15:23.383 --> 15:25.654
- You mean it this time?
- Yes.

15:25.758 --> 15:30.452
Goddamn it, yes. I can promise you.
Clouds in Oakland.

15:30.556 --> 15:32.435
All right, all right,
don't get all jittery now.

15:32.539 --> 15:35.939
Oakland.
Oakland.

15:36.768 --> 15:41.056
We're going to Oakland.
Oakland.

16:16.427 --> 16:18.918
Down and to the left.

16:42.244 --> 16:45.494
That was perfect.

16:52.421 --> 16:55.080
Yes, young Howard Hughes
has pulled it off.

16:55.184 --> 16:58.748
After two years, <i>Hell's Angels</i>
has finally finished filming.

16:58.853 --> 17:01.791
There's going to be one heck
of a wrap party in Hollywood tonight.

17:01.895 --> 17:04.880
The price tag?
A staggering $ 2 million.

17:04.984 --> 17:07.377
So, if every human being
in America buys a ticket,

17:07.482 --> 17:09.387
heck, he might
even make a profit.

17:14.401 --> 17:18.347
First the clouds don't come, then the
planes break down, then the planes crash.

17:18.451 --> 17:20.101
Then the Zeppelins don't work.

17:20.204 --> 17:23.066
Seems we've had everything but
a damn plague of locusts on this thing.

17:23.171 --> 17:24.605
I mean, you have to admit.

17:24.710 --> 17:30.493
Now, honestly, did you ever think
you'd actually finish the damn thing?

17:30.918 --> 17:32.460
Come with me.

17:34.130 --> 17:37.743
Mama, darling,
if I'm a success in this show,

17:37.847 --> 17:39.844
- well, we're going to move from here.
- Oh, no.

17:39.969 --> 17:42.000
Oh, yes.
We're gonna move up in the Bronx.

17:42.104 --> 17:44.609
Lot of nice green grass up there
and a whole lot of people you know.

17:44.713 --> 17:47.087
There's the Ginsbergs,
the Guttenbergs, and the Goldbergs.

17:47.192 --> 17:49.019
A whole lot of bergs.
I don't know them all.

17:50.437 --> 17:54.383
You see, this is what the people want.
Silent pictures are yesterday's news.

17:54.487 --> 17:58.101
So I figure we gotta reshoot
<i>Hell's Angels</i> for sound.

17:59.738 --> 18:02.647
- How much of it?
- All of it.

18:02.751 --> 18:07.897
Before you even ask, I'll tell you. An
additional 1.7 million. We got that much?

18:08.001 --> 18:11.237
- No.
- Well, we'll make it.

18:11.342 --> 18:13.365
Take care of that, would you?

18:13.469 --> 18:14.659
Now get this.

18:24.972 --> 18:29.173
In the halls of 7000 Romaine, it goes on
day after day, month after month.

18:29.277 --> 18:33.135
Howard Hughes is now editing
some 25 miles of film.

18:34.899 --> 18:39.516
Heck, I say release it now and give
the world its first 560-hour movie.

18:39.620 --> 18:44.683
Pat. Mr Hughes needs this reel
in the projection room right now.

18:44.788 --> 18:46.482
Enough is enough, Mr Hughes.

18:46.586 --> 18:49.690
Are you ever gonna let us actually see
this little epic of yours?

18:49.795 --> 18:51.595
Hurry up.

19:12.311 --> 19:13.759
- Who is it?
- Noah.

19:13.864 --> 19:15.930
Come on in.

19:17.149 --> 19:19.485
I've been on the phone to Houston
for three solid hours.

19:19.610 --> 19:21.513
We're fixing every goddamn book we have.

19:21.617 --> 19:23.810
Wait, wait, wait.

19:23.914 --> 19:27.314
Yeah. Run reel ten again.
I think we're duplicating a shot here.

19:27.418 --> 19:31.233
And tell Jimmy I want
ten chocolate chip cookies, all right?

19:31.337 --> 19:35.031
Medium chips,
none too close to the outside. Got it?

19:36.043 --> 19:38.529
Do you remember
that goddamn shot from reel ten?

19:38.633 --> 19:43.662
No. I don't remember anything from
reel ten. I don't know what reel ten is.

19:43.766 --> 19:47.000
I'm a businessman, Howard,
and so are you.

19:47.104 --> 19:48.916
Now, look.

19:49.021 --> 19:52.960
This has been a great ride.
We've had a hell of a lot of fun.

19:53.064 --> 19:56.922
But you're losing
$ 25,000 a day doing this.

19:57.027 --> 19:59.027
Every day.

20:04.655 --> 20:07.442
So, what are my options?

20:09.034 --> 20:11.693
Well, this time I don't know
that you have any.

20:11.798 --> 20:14.862
I'm afraid you got to close it down.

20:14.966 --> 20:16.700
Dig your way out.

20:23.257 --> 20:25.788
I'm sorry, Howard.

20:25.892 --> 20:28.092
I truly am.

20:35.060 --> 20:38.429
Reel ten, Mr Hughes.

20:42.693 --> 20:45.556
Mortgage Toolco.

20:45.661 --> 20:47.974
Every asset.

20:48.079 --> 20:50.771
- You heard me.
- If you do that, you could lose everything.

20:50.875 --> 20:52.944
Well, I won't.

20:55.581 --> 20:57.181
I won't.

20:58.344 --> 21:00.344
All right.

21:01.545 --> 21:03.289
I'll get into it.

21:04.548 --> 21:06.707
Thanks, Noah.

21:41.252 --> 21:44.947
More than half a million good souls
lining the curb of Hollywood Boulevard.

21:45.051 --> 21:46.914
Look at the automobiles,
ladies and gentlemen.

21:47.018 --> 21:50.290
There are at least 45,000 cars here,
making it the greatest traffic jam...

21:50.394 --> 21:53.461
Young Howard Hughes must have
quite a lump in his throat tonight.

21:53.565 --> 21:57.590
Six months after the stock market crashes
and after the death of three of his pilots,

21:57.694 --> 22:00.798
he's finally unveiling
his $4-million baby doll.

22:00.903 --> 22:05.264
It's the most expensive movie ever.
Nothing five-and-dime for our Mr Hughes.

22:05.368 --> 22:07.474
Nothing like tonight
has ever been seen before,

22:07.578 --> 22:10.600
and I can certainly say
it will never be seen again.

22:10.704 --> 22:13.644
500,000 people are crowding the streets
to get a glimpse

22:13.749 --> 22:17.317
of the stars and celebrities.
Three companies of Marines were called

22:17.421 --> 22:21.236
to assist the 250 special police
who are handling this enormous crowd.

22:21.341 --> 22:22.904
This is an industry town, my friends,

22:23.008 --> 22:26.326
and nobody, but nobody,
makes a movie outside a studio.

22:26.430 --> 22:28.908
Sure, some Hollywood insiders
over at the Brown Derby...

22:29.012 --> 22:31.161
And now, ladies and gentlemen, I think...

22:31.265 --> 22:34.374
Yes, yes. I can just see
Mr Hughes's car arriving now.

22:34.478 --> 22:38.212
Mr Hughes escorts
the lovely starlet Jean Harlow tonight.

22:38.316 --> 22:41.965
He discovered her for this picture,
and we think her platinum-blonde locks

22:42.070 --> 22:46.724
and hot-jazz, baby-doll style
are gonna make her a big star.

23:11.842 --> 23:13.035
Mr Hughes.

23:13.139 --> 23:16.498
Mr Hughes, how about a word?

23:16.602 --> 23:21.048
Big night for you, Mr Hughes.

23:21.153 --> 23:24.051
Big night for you tonight.

23:24.156 --> 23:26.261
Very big.
Very big.

23:26.365 --> 23:30.485
Tell us what it was like
making this fabulous picture.

23:31.987 --> 23:32.787
Yes.

23:33.874 --> 23:34.874
Yeah.

23:35.417 --> 23:41.197
So, four million clams from your own
pocket. Nervous how the flick will fly?

23:43.415 --> 23:47.239
Big night.
You enjoy the show.

23:47.343 --> 23:52.830
Yes, well, let me present the feminine star
of this spectacle, <i>Hell's Angels.</i>

23:52.934 --> 23:55.411
- Miss Jean Harlow.
- Thank you.

23:55.515 --> 23:58.708
I would like to use this occasion
to publicly thank Mr Hughes

23:58.812 --> 24:02.335
for the opportunity he gave me.
Thank you.

24:02.440 --> 24:06.297
Thank you. And now
I'd like to ask Roscoe Arbuckle

24:06.401 --> 24:08.761
to introduce his pet lion cub, Gilmore.

24:08.865 --> 24:11.329
What the hell's the matter with you?
Can't you remember my name?

24:11.433 --> 24:15.731
I'm sorry. Roscoe Turner.
And this would be Gilmore.

24:58.783 --> 25:00.526
We've got him.
We've got him.

25:02.119 --> 25:05.316
Murder. That's what
this dirty rotten politician war is.

25:05.420 --> 25:07.288
Murder. You know it as well as I do.

25:45.037 --> 25:47.706
Stand up, Slim, take a bow.

26:00.177 --> 26:02.292
Reel four played way too long.
Too many coughs.

26:02.396 --> 26:04.984
Get Harry and the team out of the party,
get them over to the office.

26:05.088 --> 26:06.377
I want to cut a few shots tonight.

26:06.481 --> 26:10.299
Find Glenn Odekirk. Somebody write
this down. "Flush rivets." You got that?

26:10.403 --> 26:12.260
- Flush rivets.
- Flush rivets.

26:12.364 --> 26:14.055
Lickety split, boss.

26:14.159 --> 26:16.226
Here he is.

26:17.862 --> 26:20.264
<i>Variety</i> says,
"This one won't miss."

26:20.368 --> 26:22.644
Magnificently photographed...

26:22.749 --> 26:26.188
Scenes that never
have been approached...

26:26.292 --> 26:29.611
Not for a long time have I seen
anything as enthralling...

26:29.715 --> 26:34.665
It cost four million dollars
and it has four million thrills...

27:31.185 --> 27:37.057
The lighter shade. I don't want to look like
Boris Karloff, if you know what I mean.

27:38.108 --> 27:42.016
I read in the magazines
that you play golf.

27:42.120 --> 27:43.811
On occasion.

27:43.915 --> 27:46.397
Well, how about nine holes?

27:48.160 --> 27:50.940
Now, Mr Hughes?

27:51.044 --> 27:54.074
If it would be convenient, Miss Hepburn.

28:16.230 --> 28:19.760
You're not extending enough
on your follow-through.

28:19.864 --> 28:23.099
Follow-through is everything in golf,
just like life. Ha-ha-ha.

28:23.204 --> 28:24.350
Don't you find?

28:24.454 --> 28:26.516
Saw your <i>Scarface</i> picture.

28:26.621 --> 28:28.436
- Violent.
- Realistic.

28:28.540 --> 28:33.772
Movies are movies, Howard, not life.
Now, the stage - the stage is real.

28:33.877 --> 28:38.074
Real flesh and blood. Human beings
right up there in front of you, buster.

28:38.178 --> 28:41.282
Can't look away.
Can't munch popcorn. That would be rude.

28:41.386 --> 28:43.244
- Do you like the theatre?
- No.

28:43.349 --> 28:45.538
I adore the theatre.

28:45.643 --> 28:47.832
Only alive on stage.
I'll teach you.

28:47.937 --> 28:51.963
We'll see some Ibsen, if the Republicans
haven't outlawed him by now. Ha-ha.

28:52.067 --> 28:55.196
You're not a Republican, are you? Couldn't
abide that. How did you vote in '32?

28:55.300 --> 28:59.391
- Well, I didn't.
- You must. It's your sacred franchise.

29:02.234 --> 29:05.392
Heard you were wooing Ginger Rogers.
What about that?

29:05.496 --> 29:07.225
Aw, she's just a friend.

29:07.329 --> 29:09.937
Ha. Men can't be friends
with women, Howard.

29:10.041 --> 29:13.979
They must possess them or leave them be.
It's a primitive urge from caveman days.

29:14.084 --> 29:17.359
It's all in Darwin.
Hunt the flesh, kill the flesh, eat the flesh.

29:17.463 --> 29:21.320
That's the male sex all over.

29:21.424 --> 29:23.424
Excuse me?

29:23.594 --> 29:28.744
Well, if you're deaf you must own up to it.
Get a hearing aid, or see my father.

29:28.848 --> 29:32.540
He's a urologist, but it's all tied up
inside the body, don't you find?

29:32.644 --> 29:36.796
Me, I keep healthy.
I take seven showers a day to keep clean.

29:36.900 --> 29:40.589
Also because I am what's so
vulgarly referred to as "outdoorsy".

29:40.694 --> 29:44.552
Well, I'm not "outdoorsy".
I'm athletic. I sweat.

29:44.656 --> 29:47.432
There it is.
Now we both know the sordid truth.

29:47.536 --> 29:50.060
I sweat and you're deaf.

29:50.165 --> 29:53.526
Aren't we a fine pair of misfits?

29:56.622 --> 29:57.822
Three.

30:05.965 --> 30:08.041
Noble effort.

30:10.094 --> 30:13.373
So I suppose you're wooing me now.

30:13.477 --> 30:15.277
Oh, well.

30:34.493 --> 30:39.693
Not enough. Not enough.
These rivets have to be completely flush.

30:39.797 --> 30:42.948
I want every screw and joint countersunk.

30:43.052 --> 30:45.741
I want no wind resistance on the fuselage.

30:45.845 --> 30:49.162
She has got to be clean, Odie.
Clean. Understand?

30:49.266 --> 30:52.998
- OK, Howard.
- I don't know what else to tell you.

30:53.102 --> 30:54.333
What have you got for me?

30:54.437 --> 30:58.004
The thing is, TWA needs a new plane.
A modern plane.

30:58.108 --> 31:00.337
- Yeah? What kind of plane?
- OK.

31:00.441 --> 31:03.760
The DC-3 has 21 daytime seats
and 14 overnight berths.

31:03.864 --> 31:06.258
- Something bigger.
- Try 50 seats.

31:06.363 --> 31:09.389
- With a ceiling of 12,000 feet.
- No.

31:09.493 --> 31:13.227
20,000. Think about it, Jack.
What does 20,000 feet give you?

31:13.331 --> 31:15.774
- Less turbulence.
- Right, because it's above the weather.

31:15.878 --> 31:18.482
Jack, we want to fly above the weather.

31:18.586 --> 31:22.155
Only 1 per cent of the American population
has ever set foot on a commercial airliner.

31:22.260 --> 31:25.241
Why? Because they're scared to death,
Jack, and they should be.

31:25.345 --> 31:28.033
I mean, 7,000 feet is bumpy as shit.
You know that.

31:28.137 --> 31:30.661
We build a plane
that flies above the weather,

31:30.765 --> 31:34.620
we could get every man, woman and child
in this country to feel safe up there.

31:34.724 --> 31:37.877
An airplane with the ability
to fly in the substratosphere.

31:37.982 --> 31:41.253
Across the country.
Across the world.

31:41.357 --> 31:43.754
Now, that is the future.

31:43.858 --> 31:45.092
- You with me?
- Yeah.

31:45.196 --> 31:47.410
Shoot straight with me now,
cos I don't wanna get into all this

31:47.514 --> 31:49.261
if your board doesn't have the balls for it.

31:49.365 --> 31:52.019
- Would they support us?
- I don't know. They're tight bastards.

31:52.123 --> 31:54.146
- Well, what's your financial picture?
- Not great.

31:54.250 --> 31:56.354
- Last year's deficit?
- 770,000.

31:56.459 --> 31:59.064
- What's it selling at?
- About eight dollars a share.

31:59.169 --> 32:02.985
That's the lowest it's been.

32:03.089 --> 32:05.529
- I could do that.
- Do what?

32:05.633 --> 32:07.863
- Buy it.
- You want to buy the airline?

32:07.967 --> 32:10.787
For crying out loud, Jack. We don't want
a bunch of damn pencil-pushers

32:10.892 --> 32:13.287
getting in the way
of us making our plane, do we?

32:13.391 --> 32:18.206
Give me brass tacks, now. What does
controlling interest in TWA cost me?

32:18.311 --> 32:21.962
- Call it 15 million.
- Whew.

32:22.066 --> 32:25.013
- That is a chunk of change.
- Yeah.

32:27.773 --> 32:31.846
You call Noah Dietrich.
You have him start buying.

32:31.950 --> 32:36.267
Howard, hold on. Are you sure? You want
to think about it for five minutes?

32:36.371 --> 32:40.363
Hell, Jack, I've got a tiger by the tail here,
and I ain't gonna let it go.

32:49.170 --> 32:54.453
Good evening, Mr Hughes.
Welcome. Your table is ready.

32:54.557 --> 32:57.580
- How goes the aviation, Mr Hughes?
- Just fine, Pete.

32:57.684 --> 33:00.050
I'm so glad.

33:01.599 --> 33:04.340
- Good evening, Mr Hughes. Madame.
- It's "Miss".

33:04.444 --> 33:07.881
- Miss. The usual, Mr Hughes?
- Please, yes.

33:07.985 --> 33:10.427
And may I recommend for the lady
our clementine soup,

33:10.532 --> 33:14.431
followed by roast wild duck with currant
glaze and poached pears in rose sauce?

33:14.536 --> 33:17.731
- It's truly divine.
- Yeah. That sounds fine.

33:19.700 --> 33:23.562
Your kind of a joint, is it?

33:23.667 --> 33:26.110
- Wouldn't have thought.
- They're open late.

33:26.214 --> 33:30.069
I go to a hot dog stand on La Cienega, too.
They're open till about four.

33:30.173 --> 33:31.973
Are they?

33:33.464 --> 33:35.919
How marvellous.

33:51.148 --> 33:54.140
Howard. Howard.

33:54.244 --> 33:56.598
Hi. Son of a gun.

33:56.703 --> 34:00.602
Kate, this is Johnny Meyer. I suppose
you could call him my press agent.

34:00.707 --> 34:02.420
Pleased to meet you.
Loved you in <i>Alice Adams.</i>

34:02.524 --> 34:04.314
- You're too kind.
- I'm sure you know Errol, right?

34:04.419 --> 34:07.153
- Mr Flynn. Yes.
- Kate. Kate.

34:07.257 --> 34:11.320
Kate of the clenched-jawed Hepburns.
Enchanting as always.

34:11.425 --> 34:13.782
You should use Lux on your hands,
by the way. I do.

34:13.887 --> 34:17.080
Kate, sweetie, you and Howard ought
to cook up a picture. Co-star with Errol...

34:17.185 --> 34:18.751
My chair.

34:22.304 --> 34:25.667
I think not.
Don't you read <i>Variety.</i> Mr Meyer?

34:25.771 --> 34:29.422
I'm box-office poison.
I'm on the outs, the skids, the doldrums.

34:29.527 --> 34:33.260
Washed up, day-old fish
not worth the eating, so they tell me.

34:33.364 --> 34:36.887
To hell with them. To hell with them,
my dear. Soulless pricks to a man, right?

34:36.991 --> 34:43.273
Johnny tells me you're thinking about
doing a Western, of all goddamn things.

34:45.286 --> 34:48.065
Are you making a Western, Howard?

34:48.170 --> 34:50.777
Yeah. Making a Western.
I'm gonna call it <i>The Outlaw.</i>

34:50.882 --> 34:55.114
Yeah. And you know what it's about?
S-e-x. It's all about s-e-x.

34:55.219 --> 34:56.949
It's a Western.

34:57.054 --> 35:01.204
- You can't have fornication in a Western.
- It's not real sex, Skinny. It's movie sex.

35:01.308 --> 35:05.042
What <i>Scarface</i> did for the gangster picture,
<i>The Outlaw</i> is gonna do for the Western.

35:05.146 --> 35:08.086
Put the sex and guts and blood
right up there on the screen...

35:08.190 --> 35:10.298
- Have any cigarettes?
- Don't mind us.

35:10.402 --> 35:13.840
New York-cut steak, 12 peas,
bottle of milk with the cap on.

35:13.945 --> 35:17.219
You're the only movie star I know
can't afford his own goddamn cigarettes.

35:17.323 --> 35:21.686
I hope your food isn't getting cold over
at your table somewhere, or something.

35:21.790 --> 35:24.183
No, no, no. We're here all night.
Don't worry.

35:24.287 --> 35:27.857
Now, Howard.
Now, Howard, Howard. Howard.

35:27.962 --> 35:31.361
If you're seriously talking about putting
carnality back on the silver screen,

35:31.465 --> 35:36.035
you must swear to let me in
on the casting sessions.

35:37.922 --> 35:41.119
I've somewhat of an eye -
an eye for talent, isn't that right, Johnny?

35:41.223 --> 35:43.792
You ought to give up that prancing
in tights, be a talent scout.

35:43.896 --> 35:48.087
That prancing in tights paid for my new
yacht. You must all come sailing with me.

35:48.191 --> 35:49.756
Catalina, this weekend.
What do you say?

35:49.861 --> 35:52.087
- Yeah, Catalina. Sounds grand.
- Let's have some fun.

35:52.191 --> 35:54.845
I've even managed to coax
the luscious Miss de Havilland

35:54.949 --> 35:57.219
and her equally luscious sister
to accompany me.

35:57.323 --> 35:59.537
Though I fear their mother
will insist on coming along

35:59.641 --> 36:02.141
to preserve their questionable virtue.

36:02.245 --> 36:06.938
We shall assault these twin monuments
of pristine Britannic beauty nonetheless.

36:07.042 --> 36:09.187
- What do you say, Howard?
- Yeah?

36:09.292 --> 36:10.690
- Yeah.
- Yeah?

36:10.794 --> 36:11.794
Yeah.

36:16.127 --> 36:18.447
I gotta... I gotta go.

36:18.551 --> 36:21.743
If you'll excuse us,
we have to be somewhere.

36:21.847 --> 36:24.620
You are somewhere, Howard,
you madman.

36:24.725 --> 36:27.749
- Somewhere else. Excuse us.
- Charmed, gentlemen.

36:27.853 --> 36:32.131
Do help yourself to the poached pears.
I hear they're divine.

36:32.235 --> 36:35.756
Well. Howard Hughes,
ladies and gentlemen.

36:35.860 --> 36:37.176
Was that meant for me?

36:37.280 --> 36:40.719
My hero.
God, all that Hollywood talk bores me silly.

36:40.823 --> 36:43.852
As if there aren't more important things
in the world. Mussolini, for one.

36:43.956 --> 36:48.022
- Where are we going, by the way?
- Do you feel like a little adventure?

36:48.126 --> 36:50.148
Do your worst, Mr Hughes.

36:50.252 --> 36:51.520
...you limey bastard.

36:51.625 --> 36:54.484
I'm a Tasmanian bastard,
you ignorant prick.

36:54.588 --> 36:56.658
That a way, Errol.

37:30.534 --> 37:33.314
That's Mr Mayer's house right there.

37:33.418 --> 37:36.698
Do you know where Jack Warner lives?

37:44.632 --> 37:48.494
- What's that on the steering wheel?
- Cellophane.

37:48.598 --> 37:52.878
If you had any idea of the crap
that people carry around on their hands...

37:52.983 --> 37:55.293
What kind of crap?

37:55.398 --> 37:57.599
You don't want to know.

38:02.233 --> 38:05.103
Hold onto the wheel for a bit.

38:12.409 --> 38:14.651
That's too hard.
Relax your hand. Relax your hand.

38:21.127 --> 38:26.282
You see, you've got to feel the vibration
of the engine through your fingertips.

38:26.386 --> 38:29.745
- Feel that?
- Yes.

38:29.849 --> 38:30.849
Yeah.

38:31.979 --> 38:34.169
Well, that's good.

38:34.273 --> 38:35.473
Golly.

38:40.437 --> 38:42.340
Well, she's all yours.

38:42.445 --> 38:46.929
- Where are you going?
- I think there's some milk back here.

38:47.034 --> 38:50.942
- You just keep us steady now.
- All right.

39:08.966 --> 39:10.748
- Howard.
- Yeah?

39:10.852 --> 39:13.245
There's a rather alarming mountain
heading our way.

39:13.350 --> 39:16.216
Pull back on the wheel a smidge.
Go on.

39:20.811 --> 39:22.011
Golly.

39:29.361 --> 39:35.067
I don't think I've ever met someone
who actually uses the word "golly".

39:41.457 --> 39:43.737
You all right?
Do you want me to take over?

39:43.842 --> 39:47.702
Just when I'm getting the hang of it?

39:51.509 --> 39:55.458
- You... You want some milk?
- Please.

40:17.159 --> 40:21.066
Utterly smashing.
We'll do it again. I'm free Wednesday.

40:21.171 --> 40:23.030
It's a little early for golf, though,
don't you think?

40:23.134 --> 40:25.489
Oh, no. I live right there.

40:25.594 --> 40:28.419
- Feel like a drink?
- Lead on.

40:29.463 --> 40:32.993
Now, that makes
for a challenging par four.

40:33.097 --> 40:37.209
My decorator picked out
the wallpaper and such.

40:37.314 --> 40:42.421
He's queer as a bed bug, but...
I just hate this room.

40:42.525 --> 40:44.755
Gives me the willies. Ugh.

40:44.859 --> 40:49.017
Feel I'm about to be swallowed up
by the latest issue of <i>Town & Country.</i>

40:57.575 --> 41:00.605
What room do you like?

41:00.709 --> 41:02.509
My study.

41:04.457 --> 41:06.533
Take me there.

41:22.641 --> 41:26.382
You are the tallest woman I know.

41:26.486 --> 41:29.093
And all sharp elbows and knees.

41:29.197 --> 41:30.597
Beware.

41:53.172 --> 41:56.208
Will you fly me to work tomorrow?

41:58.803 --> 42:01.638
It is tomorrow.

42:53.566 --> 42:55.264
Keep your eye on the fuel gauge.

42:55.368 --> 42:58.972
She's got a minimum of fuel to keep
her weight down. Two runs, that's it.

42:59.076 --> 43:02.126
After that, you're flying on vapours.
And then you crash and then you die.

43:02.231 --> 43:03.898
- Right.
- Just give her easy flying.

43:04.002 --> 43:06.856
Don't worry about speed.
And don't think about the record today.

43:06.960 --> 43:10.301
I wish to God you'd let someone else take
her up. You've got damn 20 test pilots...

43:10.405 --> 43:13.366
Hell, why should I let
someone else have all the fun?

43:13.470 --> 43:16.248
See you in a bit.

43:36.275 --> 43:37.875
Contact.

45:05.614 --> 45:07.414
Whoo-hoo.

45:07.750 --> 45:08.550
339.

45:10.911 --> 45:12.074
Goddamn.

45:34.518 --> 45:35.318
347.

45:36.654 --> 45:38.887
Whoo.
Son of a bitch.

46:11.347 --> 46:13.947
- 352.
- 352.

46:15.100 --> 46:16.345
Good girl.

46:25.945 --> 46:27.545
Damn it.

46:31.450 --> 46:34.647
Goddamn it.
Oh, God.

46:34.751 --> 46:38.244
- There goes our meal ticket.
- Come on.

47:18.122 --> 47:20.402
Howard. Howard.

47:20.507 --> 47:22.946
How did we do?

47:23.051 --> 47:26.989
352 on the last run.

47:27.093 --> 47:28.797
She'll go faster.

47:29.300 --> 47:31.580
Country mouse.

47:31.684 --> 47:33.164
Kate. Katie.

47:33.268 --> 47:35.338
Upstairs, city mouse.

47:38.017 --> 47:39.217
Hello.

47:39.486 --> 47:43.716
- Good Lord, what happened to you?
- Nothing. Hard landing. I cut my foot.

47:43.820 --> 47:46.677
Sit down. I'll take care of it.
You tell me everything.

47:46.782 --> 47:50.516
Well, you cannot imagine what it was like,
Katie. You cannot imagine the speed.

47:50.620 --> 47:52.682
She was like a winged bullet up there.

47:52.787 --> 47:56.854
- What did she make?
- Around...

47:56.959 --> 47:57.759
352.

48:05.377 --> 48:07.577
You did it.

48:08.141 --> 48:10.078
Fastest man on the planet.

48:10.182 --> 48:14.625
- Hot dog. I'm so proud of you.
- She did it, baby.

48:14.729 --> 48:18.255
- You knew she would.
- She was fine. She was just fine.

48:20.392 --> 48:22.848
- Now let me see your foot.
- Yeah.

48:23.813 --> 48:25.595
Good God.
You're covered in blood.

48:25.699 --> 48:28.886
No, no. That's just beet juice.
I crashed into a beet field.

48:28.991 --> 48:32.816
- What?
- Yeah, I crashed in a beet field.

48:35.324 --> 48:38.232
Let me get you cleaned up.

48:38.336 --> 48:40.442
Heavens, what is this?
Electrical tape?

48:40.546 --> 48:43.900
Yeah. Odie just sort of slammed it on there.

48:44.005 --> 48:50.038
But all I could think about was
getting home to see you.

48:53.676 --> 48:57.294
I am so proud of you.

49:01.100 --> 49:03.170
Now, this is going to sting a little bit.

