to a different dazzling event.
The TWA king always talks up his airline

01:08:26.981 --> 01:08:29.845
as he escorts a succession...

01:08:31.895 --> 01:08:35.425
The Hercules, ladies and gentlemen.
The Hercules.

01:08:35.529 --> 01:08:39.596
A plane, a boat, a flying city.

01:08:39.701 --> 01:08:43.019
Now, don't forget. Every bill comes to me.
They don't pay for anything.

01:08:43.124 --> 01:08:46.772
Those men decide whether or not to fund
the plane, so I need them real happy.

01:08:46.876 --> 01:08:49.399
- You do what it takes.
- You betcha, boss.

01:08:49.504 --> 01:08:52.111
What about the girls?
How are they in the bomb department?

01:08:52.215 --> 01:08:56.198
Well, let's put it this way.
It'll be a regular boob buffet.

01:08:56.301 --> 01:08:59.662
I don't think the gentlemen from the Air
Corps will have any trouble scoring tonight.

01:08:59.767 --> 01:09:05.372
And inside, 700 brave American soldiers,
a dozen Sherman tanks,

01:09:05.477 --> 01:09:10.542
all winging their way over the Atlantic,
free from the threats of the U-boats below.

01:09:10.647 --> 01:09:15.133
Could Jules Verne himself have ever
imagined anything so magnificent?

01:09:15.237 --> 01:09:19.093
Could he have imagined her mammoth
wingspan, longer than a football field?

01:09:19.197 --> 01:09:21.095
Don't you see how this demeans me?

01:09:21.200 --> 01:09:23.103
Since when do you care about
the scandal rags?

01:09:23.207 --> 01:09:27.059
Every time there's a picture of you with
another woman, it's like a slap in the face.

01:09:27.162 --> 01:09:30.234
- Don't you understand that?
- That's overstating it just a bit.

01:09:30.337 --> 01:09:33.737
Joan Crawford, Ginger Rogers,
Linda Darnell, Joan Fontaine,

01:09:33.841 --> 01:09:36.832
and now Bette Davis, for God's sake.

01:09:38.546 --> 01:09:43.884
Look. They're Cracker Jack candy, honey.
They don't mean anything to me.

01:09:44.885 --> 01:09:46.885
Very nice.

01:09:48.305 --> 01:09:51.546
Well, you're the one that said
that all men are predators, right?

01:09:51.649 --> 01:09:54.589
I mean, it's all in Darwin.
Remember?

01:09:54.693 --> 01:09:58.632
And am I to expect this behaviour
to continue after the wedding?

01:09:58.737 --> 01:10:05.269
What is really bothering you, Kate?
Is it the women? Or the publicity?

01:10:09.368 --> 01:10:13.911
Can't you eat ice cream from a bowl
like everyone else in the world?

01:10:20.713 --> 01:10:23.713
Don't you dare.

01:10:35.895 --> 01:10:36.895
Yeah.

01:10:38.401 --> 01:10:42.092
No. Odie, this is not a good time.

01:10:42.197 --> 01:10:46.432
For Christ's sakes, we can't make the
Hercules if we don't have any aluminum.

01:10:46.537 --> 01:10:49.727
Wait. No, no.
I can hear you better now.

01:10:49.831 --> 01:10:54.858
Look, you tell the War Production Board
that this is an essential strategic operation.

01:10:54.963 --> 01:10:57.427
Odie, if they're giving aluminum
to Douglas, Northrop and Boeing,

01:10:57.531 --> 01:10:59.571
they sure as hell
can give some to Hughes Aircraft.

01:10:59.676 --> 01:11:02.865
Don't set the ice cream...

01:11:02.970 --> 01:11:04.684
Meantime, we've got to think
of something else.

01:11:04.788 --> 01:11:07.290
If we can't get aluminum,
we'll just have to find another way.

01:11:07.394 --> 01:11:09.083
Christ, I don't know.
You tell me.

01:11:09.187 --> 01:11:14.000
We'll find some alloy that works
just as well. Right. Look...

01:11:14.105 --> 01:11:16.300
If we can't get any aluminum,
we'll just have to use wood.

01:11:16.404 --> 01:11:18.505
You can't make
a 200-ton plane out of wood.

01:11:18.609 --> 01:11:20.971
Why the hell not?
The damn thing is a flying boat, right?

01:11:21.075 --> 01:11:22.952
- What do they use to make boats out of?
- Oak.

01:11:23.056 --> 01:11:26.180
Think of the Hercules
like a flying Spanish galleon.

01:11:26.285 --> 01:11:29.558
Spanish galleons could weigh 1,200 tons.

01:11:29.662 --> 01:11:32.226
Good luck today.

01:11:32.330 --> 01:11:35.650
We just have to find the right kind of wood.
Something light but strong.

01:11:35.754 --> 01:11:38.747
- Morning, Kate.
- Pine, cedar, maybe birch.

01:11:49.093 --> 01:11:50.293
Catch.

01:11:54.598 --> 01:11:56.879
From my farm.

01:11:56.983 --> 01:11:59.930
If you like it,
I can get you a bushel.

01:12:12.366 --> 01:12:15.284
Trouble with Mr Hughes?

01:12:20.040 --> 01:12:24.749
There's too much Howard Hughes
in Howard Hughes.

01:12:26.422 --> 01:12:28.498
That's the trouble.

01:12:41.770 --> 01:12:43.770
Beautiful.

01:12:45.608 --> 01:12:48.222
Don't you even take Christmas off?

01:12:48.326 --> 01:12:51.099
Nice to see you, Bob.
Sorry, I've got grease on my hands.

01:12:51.203 --> 01:12:53.770
Have we got something to show you?

01:12:57.953 --> 01:13:03.653
Take a look. She's the XF-11
reconnaissance flier. Spy plane, really.

01:13:03.757 --> 01:13:06.531
Designed every inch of her myself.

01:13:06.635 --> 01:13:08.782
She's got a top speed of 450,

01:13:08.886 --> 01:13:11.706
which means she can outrun
anything they throw against her.

01:13:11.810 --> 01:13:14.958
After the Japs stole my H-1 design
for their goddamn Zeros,

01:13:15.062 --> 01:13:18.167
I figured I needed to do them one better.

01:13:18.272 --> 01:13:21.589
Yeah. She's my Buck Rogers ship.

01:13:21.694 --> 01:13:23.883
She's a looker.

01:13:23.988 --> 01:13:26.055
OK, what have you got for me?

01:13:33.239 --> 01:13:35.686
Jiminy Cricket.

01:13:35.790 --> 01:13:39.523
Seating capacity for 60.
Wingspan, 123 feet.

01:13:39.627 --> 01:13:42.983
Four double Cyclone engines.
Her ceiling's 25,000 feet.

01:13:43.087 --> 01:13:46.406
- Gross weight?
- 86,000. Wing loading of 41 pounds.

01:13:46.510 --> 01:13:49.410
So less drag on the plane in thinner air.

01:13:49.514 --> 01:13:53.956
At high cruise power, you're looking
at a top speed of around 340.

01:13:54.060 --> 01:13:58.668
Giving her a range of about 3,000 miles.

01:13:58.772 --> 01:14:01.801
- Cross-country.
- Nonstop.

01:14:02.601 --> 01:14:04.838
Bob, you know something?

01:14:04.942 --> 01:14:07.642
You are a son of a bitch.

01:14:19.535 --> 01:14:22.240
Bob, you got something on your suit.

01:14:23.497 --> 01:14:24.497
Yeah.

01:14:25.255 --> 01:14:29.828
On your lapel there.
You got something on your lapel.

01:14:30.880 --> 01:14:32.956
Right there, Bob.

01:14:34.550 --> 01:14:38.207
You missed it.
Right there.

01:14:38.311 --> 01:14:40.418
Clean it off, would you?

01:14:40.523 --> 01:14:43.123
Here. Thanks.

01:14:46.270 --> 01:14:49.271
Now throw it away.

01:14:51.817 --> 01:14:54.355
No, over there.

01:14:59.617 --> 01:15:03.607
Thanks.
So, what do you call her?

01:15:03.711 --> 01:15:05.984
The Constellation.
But we can change that.

01:15:06.089 --> 01:15:07.863
No, no, no.

01:15:07.968 --> 01:15:10.628
It's pretty. I like her.

01:15:11.796 --> 01:15:15.786
So, what kind of deal can you give me?
What kind of deal can you give me?

01:15:15.890 --> 01:15:18.452
We'll give you the first 40 planes
off the assembly line.

01:15:18.556 --> 01:15:21.038
That should give us
about two years exclusivity with her?

01:15:21.142 --> 01:15:22.587
Hell, more than that.

01:15:22.691 --> 01:15:26.754
United and American don't have
the imagination for a plane like this.

01:15:26.858 --> 01:15:29.972
Two years ahead of Juan Trippe, then.

01:15:34.527 --> 01:15:38.275
- How much?
- 450,000 each.

01:15:38.906 --> 01:15:42.646
That's 18 million for the first 40.

01:15:42.750 --> 01:15:48.200
Hell, TWA can't afford that.
The damn airline's flat broke.

01:15:49.875 --> 01:15:52.580
Guess I'll just have
to pay for them myself.

01:15:53.295 --> 01:15:56.409
Build them, Bob.
Send the bill to Noah Dietrich.

01:15:56.513 --> 01:15:58.250
And thank you.

01:16:01.846 --> 01:16:03.832
Merry Christmas.

01:16:03.936 --> 01:16:07.560
You have just placed the largest order for
airplanes in the history of the damn planet.

01:16:08.435 --> 01:16:10.302
Lockheed just sent us a bill for $18 million.

01:16:10.406 --> 01:16:13.970
Now now, don't get all hysterical on me,
Noah. It isn't good for you.

01:16:14.074 --> 01:16:17.761
- This is a lot of money for some planes.
- Yes. Yes, I know it's a lot of money.

01:16:17.866 --> 01:16:21.518
It's too damn much. You think I've just got
$18 million in petty cash?

01:16:21.623 --> 01:16:23.690
I should have told you earlier.
It slipped my mind.

01:16:23.795 --> 01:16:26.401
- Slipped your mind? For God's sake.
- Right. Well, look...

01:16:26.506 --> 01:16:30.274
- How could $18 million slip your mind?
- I'll get back to you. Goodbye, now.

01:16:30.378 --> 01:16:33.624
Hey, honey.
What are you doing home?

01:16:37.882 --> 01:16:41.789
You're not one for tears
and, well, neither am I.

01:16:41.893 --> 01:16:45.337
So it's best to come out with it.

01:16:48.309 --> 01:16:53.054
I've met someone.
I've fallen in love and I'm moving out.

01:16:55.274 --> 01:16:59.930
If I could make it any more gentle, I would.

01:17:00.034 --> 01:17:02.434
But I can't.

01:17:02.747 --> 01:17:06.405
So there we both are.

01:17:10.706 --> 01:17:12.654
Let's be honest.

01:17:12.758 --> 01:17:17.240
It's all been a grand adventure,
but it couldn't possibly last.

01:17:17.344 --> 01:17:21.335
We're too alike, you and I.

01:17:23.344 --> 01:17:26.623
- You met someone?
- Someone more appropriate.

01:17:26.727 --> 01:17:28.928
To me, I mean.

01:17:31.602 --> 01:17:34.549
What does that mean,
more appropriate?

01:17:34.653 --> 01:17:39.219
Someone more attuned to my needs.

01:17:39.323 --> 01:17:42.936
Look at me, Katie.
Stop acting.

01:17:44.615 --> 01:17:46.691
I'm not acting.

01:17:51.330 --> 01:17:54.117
I wonder if you even know any more.

01:17:58.879 --> 01:18:00.955
Don't be unkind.

01:18:03.759 --> 01:18:04.959
You...

01:18:06.855 --> 01:18:09.855
You want to go?

01:18:11.809 --> 01:18:13.009
Go on.

01:18:14.360 --> 01:18:18.048
Actresses are cheap in this town, darling.
I got a lot of money.

01:18:18.153 --> 01:18:22.600
- Howard, please. This is beneath you.
- No, no, this is exactly me.

01:18:22.704 --> 01:18:25.604
You come in here out of the blue and
tell me you're leaving me just like that,

01:18:25.708 --> 01:18:27.933
and you have the nerve
to expect graciousness?

01:18:28.038 --> 01:18:33.483
I expect a little maturity. I expect you
to face the situation like an adult who...

01:18:33.587 --> 01:18:37.443
Don't talk down to me.
Don't you ever talk down to me.

01:18:37.547 --> 01:18:40.912
You are a movie star, nothing more.

01:19:52.952 --> 01:19:56.071
Don't answer it.

01:19:57.581 --> 01:19:59.446
What is it, Howard?

01:19:59.550 --> 01:20:01.550
Hey, Noah.

01:20:01.716 --> 01:20:04.951
I need you to get to Penney's
and buy me new clothes.

01:20:05.055 --> 01:20:07.078
- Penney's isn't open.
- Shit.

01:20:07.183 --> 01:20:11.497
- It's two in the morning.
- Yeah, that's right. Ah, well.

01:20:11.602 --> 01:20:13.086
First thing tomorrow, then, all right?

01:20:13.191 --> 01:20:16.210
I need two suits off the rack.
One light and one dark.

01:20:16.315 --> 01:20:19.755
Three white shirts and three pairs
of white tennis shoes. You got that?

01:20:19.859 --> 01:20:22.929
- Yeah.
- No, no. Make it Woolworths.

01:20:23.033 --> 01:20:26.553
- Woolworths.
- No, no. Penney's. Penney's.

01:20:26.657 --> 01:20:28.932
All right, then.

01:20:29.037 --> 01:20:32.520
I'll get into it as soon as I can, Howard.

01:20:32.625 --> 01:20:35.940
- Noah, do you have a recorder?
- No.

01:20:36.045 --> 01:20:39.566
- Are you recording this conversation?
- No.

01:20:39.670 --> 01:20:40.270
OK.

01:20:41.468 --> 01:20:43.868
I trust you.

01:20:44.010 --> 01:20:44.868
Howard...

01:20:44.972 --> 01:20:47.742
Listen, I need those suits
first thing tomorrow, all right?

01:20:47.846 --> 01:20:49.033
- All right.
- Wait, wait.

01:20:49.137 --> 01:20:52.290
- Did I say Penney's or Woolworths?
- Penney's.

01:20:52.394 --> 01:20:56.135
- Better make it Sears.
- All right, then. Sears.

01:20:59.643 --> 01:21:01.719
I'm sorry, honey.

01:21:02.980 --> 01:21:05.388
If I don't answer,
he'll just call back.

01:21:26.962 --> 01:21:30.581
Stop there, if you please,
Miss Domergue.

01:21:35.805 --> 01:21:39.628
Have you had surgery, Miss Domergue?

01:21:39.732 --> 01:21:40.332
No.

01:21:42.110 --> 01:21:45.353
Do you have scars of any kind?

01:21:46.565 --> 01:21:47.165
No.

01:21:49.777 --> 01:21:52.315
Wipe off your lipstick.

01:21:56.492 --> 01:21:59.189
That's much better.

01:21:59.294 --> 01:22:04.411
Now, you understand that you'd be
under contract to me, personally?

01:22:05.209 --> 01:22:07.700
Do you know what that means?

01:22:15.928 --> 01:22:18.633
Turn around for me.

01:22:25.896 --> 01:22:27.896
Very nice.

01:22:28.321 --> 01:22:30.641
You move well.

01:22:32.945 --> 01:22:36.602
You live with your family, do you?

01:22:36.706 --> 01:22:37.506
Yes.

01:22:39.289 --> 01:22:41.689
That's nice.

01:22:42.169 --> 01:22:45.109
Tell me something.

01:22:45.214 --> 01:22:47.745
How old are you, Miss Domergue?

01:22:50.463 --> 01:22:51.063
15.

01:22:55.676 --> 01:22:58.001
Holy mother of God.

01:23:16.322 --> 01:23:20.439
Well, a car picks me up
every morning at eight, and off I go.

01:23:20.544 --> 01:23:26.361
I am getting my high-school diploma.
Howard thinks that education is important.

01:23:26.465 --> 01:23:28.777
- That's right.
- And then after classes,

01:23:28.881 --> 01:23:32.450
I'm off for elocution
and grooming and fittings.

01:23:32.555 --> 01:23:34.622
Well, blow me down.

01:23:35.716 --> 01:23:38.166
Don't tell me Pan Am's
working out of the Cocoanut Grove now?

01:23:38.271 --> 01:23:40.208
- Hello, Jack.
- Hello, Juan.

01:23:40.312 --> 01:23:41.958
Helen, good to see you.

01:23:42.062 --> 01:23:44.670
- How are you, Howard?
- Good, thanks.

01:23:44.774 --> 01:23:48.590
- This is Miss Faith Domergue.
- Sit down. Now, what you doing out here?

01:23:48.695 --> 01:23:51.679
Well, I'm out this way to meet
with Douglas about the DC-4.

01:23:51.783 --> 01:23:55.681
That's our new plane
and it is gonna be a pip, let me tell you.

01:23:55.785 --> 01:23:59.224
- How's the Constellation coming?
- Good.

01:23:59.328 --> 01:24:00.528
Great.

01:24:01.875 --> 01:24:04.619
So, how about letting me steal a peek?

01:24:06.455 --> 01:24:08.403
Don't think so.

01:24:08.507 --> 01:24:12.361
You know, I should be cross with you.
You stole Ray Loewy from us.

01:24:12.465 --> 01:24:14.328
He's doing our interior design.
That's right.

01:24:14.432 --> 01:24:16.913
He was doing ours.

01:24:18.467 --> 01:24:21.459
So, what are your colours?

01:24:21.563 --> 01:24:23.345
Stop fishing.

01:24:24.974 --> 01:24:29.130
So, you have buttons or zippers?

01:24:29.234 --> 01:24:30.888
I'm sorry?

01:24:32.690 --> 01:24:34.510
Buttons or zippers?

01:24:34.615 --> 01:24:37.775
For the drapes on the sleeping berths.

01:24:40.156 --> 01:24:41.756
Zippers.

01:24:50.624 --> 01:24:52.224
Buttons?

01:25:01.927 --> 01:25:05.002
So, I suppose you'll be
expanding on down to Mexico.

01:25:05.107 --> 01:25:08.294
- Why do you say that?
- Well, your range is 3,000 miles.

01:25:08.398 --> 01:25:11.339
I would imagine you'd expand
from Los Angeles to Mexico.

01:25:11.443 --> 01:25:14.716
- And maybe on down to South America.
- Hey, that's a good idea.

01:25:14.820 --> 01:25:18.267
- Anyone got a pen?
- Or across the Atlantic.

01:25:20.446 --> 01:25:23.892
Now, honey, you've had enough of this
ice cream. You give me that spoon.

01:25:23.996 --> 01:25:27.407
You don't want to get your gloves all sticky.

01:25:28.454 --> 01:25:30.493
Isn't that too far?

01:25:35.461 --> 01:25:39.126
New York to Newfoundland...

01:25:40.382 --> 01:25:42.873
to Ireland...

01:25:46.597 --> 01:25:48.397
to Paris.

01:25:55.314 --> 01:25:56.314
Well,

01:25:57.572 --> 01:26:01.767
Pan Am welcomes you.
We're overbooked as it is.

01:26:01.872 --> 01:26:05.519
It's such a burden doing it all on your own,
let me tell you.

01:26:05.623 --> 01:26:07.814
So, when's the Connie gonna be ready?

01:26:07.918 --> 01:26:10.607
- Next year, maybe. DC-4?
- Next year.

01:26:10.712 --> 01:26:13.984
Well, we look forward to her, then.

01:26:14.088 --> 01:26:17.037
And I to the Connie.

01:26:17.878 --> 01:26:21.785
I've ordered the next 40 after you.

01:26:21.890 --> 01:26:23.203
It's Miss?

01:26:23.308 --> 01:26:24.854
- Domergue.
- Domergue. Yes, of course.

01:26:24.958 --> 01:26:27.502
Now, was that a rumba or a samba
you were doing out there, my dear?

01:26:27.607 --> 01:26:30.543
- It was a samba.
- A samba, yes.

01:26:30.647 --> 01:26:33.975
Howard, I never knew
you were such a good dancer.

01:26:34.812 --> 01:26:37.054
Helen, Jack.

01:26:38.482 --> 01:26:41.890
Good going, boss. You just gave away
our entire postwar strategy.

01:26:41.994 --> 01:26:43.889
- He can't stop us.
- He's Pan Am, Howard.

01:26:43.993 --> 01:26:46.276
He can stop anything.

01:26:47.992 --> 01:26:49.775
Waiter, give me
the largest Scotch you've got.

01:26:49.879 --> 01:26:54.489
I don't know what in the hell you're
so goddamn giddy about. Excuse me.

01:28:45.609 --> 01:28:46.609
Jack.

01:28:47.162 --> 01:28:49.770
All right. I want you to get in touch
with Mr Joyce and Mr Berg.

01:28:49.874 --> 01:28:51.084
Those are my boys in Washington.

01:28:51.188 --> 01:28:53.649
Set up a meeting with Jesse Jones,
he's the secretary of commerce.

01:28:53.753 --> 01:28:55.149
- Old golfing buddy.
- Slow down.

01:28:55.253 --> 01:28:57.646
We're gonna need terminals
in both Ireland and France,

01:28:57.751 --> 01:28:59.175
and I want to get tax breaks from them.

01:28:59.279 --> 01:29:02.238
If that shit-ass thinks that he owns
the entire goddamn world,

01:29:02.343 --> 01:29:04.618
- he's got another think coming.
- Pan Am owns Europe, you know.

01:29:04.722 --> 01:29:06.119
He's smart.
We ought to think about Mexico.

01:29:06.224 --> 01:29:07.225
To hell with Mexico, Jack.

01:29:07.329 --> 01:29:10.203
No one airline should have
a monopoly on flying the Atlantic.

01:29:10.307 --> 01:29:13.792
For Christ's sakes, it isn't fair. Look,
he owns Pan Am. He owns Congress.

01:29:13.896 --> 01:29:17.878
He owns the Civil Aeronautics Board,
but he does not own the sky.

01:29:17.982 --> 01:29:20.968
We are in a street fight with that
son of a bitch now, and I'm not gonna lose.

01:29:21.072 --> 01:29:24.424
I've been fighting high-hat, Ivy-League
pricks like him my whole goddamn life.

01:29:24.528 --> 01:29:28.302
And listen, fire Ray Loewy.
You goddamn heard me? Fire Ray Loewy.

01:29:28.406 --> 01:29:31.726
He's spying for Trippe. That shit-heel
knew all about the goddamn buttons.

01:29:31.831 --> 01:29:35.820
Spies in my midst, Jack.
Spies in my midst.

01:29:50.841 --> 01:29:54.293
- Hello, Howard.
- Roland.

01:29:55.638 --> 01:29:59.089
So, what can I do for you?

01:30:02.186 --> 01:30:06.220
I want all the pictures you have
of Kate Hepburn and Spencer Tracy.

01:30:06.324 --> 01:30:09.928
All the negatives.
And I want you to kill the story.

01:30:10.032 --> 01:30:13.435
Howard, he's a married man.
He's a Catholic.

01:30:13.539 --> 01:30:17.480
They're both movie stars.
Fair game all around.

01:30:24.291 --> 01:30:27.366
My office knows where I am, Howard.

01:30:27.471 --> 01:30:30.369
I'm not gonna kill you, Roland.

01:30:30.474 --> 01:30:32.920
I don't do that.

01:30:37.138 --> 01:30:39.925
- How much?
- Not for sale.

01:30:42.685 --> 01:30:44.485
How much?

01:30:45.487 --> 01:30:48.087
Not for sale.

01:30:51.861 --> 01:30:55.768
You ever cheat on your wife, Roland?

01:30:55.872 --> 01:30:58.895
You ever screw a coloured girl?

01:30:58.999 --> 01:31:02.409
You ever steal anything?
You ever hurt anyone?

01:31:04.331 --> 01:31:06.529
Good night, Howard.

01:31:06.634 --> 01:31:10.955
You ever go to
a Communist Party meeting, Roland?

01:31:19.388 --> 01:31:21.388
TWA stock.

01:31:22.606 --> 01:31:24.406
How much?

01:31:25.445 --> 01:31:29.136
- 50,000 shares.
- Ten.

01:31:32.067 --> 01:31:34.067
All right.

01:31:36.697 --> 01:31:38.434
This isn't gonna be that easy.

01:31:38.539 --> 01:31:42.107
He's been making big contributions
on both sides of the aisle.

01:31:42.211 --> 01:31:45.816
And Jack Frye is out there lobbying
everybody in town.

01:31:45.920 --> 01:31:49.949
The French and British ambassadors
are all lined up on his side now.

01:31:50.053 --> 01:31:54.078
I'm telling you, TWA is serious
about going international.

01:31:54.182 --> 01:31:58.957
OK. Point, Mr Hughes.
Very well. You know what I think?

01:31:59.061 --> 01:32:01.712
I think it's time for you to introduce
the Community Airline Bill

01:32:01.816 --> 01:32:04.128
on the floor of the Senate.

01:32:04.232 --> 01:32:07.004
- Is it done?
- My people are finishing it right now.

01:32:07.109 --> 01:32:13.223
I also have to get you on the committee
investigating the national defence.

01:32:14.193 --> 01:32:17.434
On the committee or chairman?

01:32:17.538 --> 01:32:20.309
You know, I could be
much more effective as chairman.

01:32:20.414 --> 01:32:24.186
It's a great public platform.
You know, it generates a lot of press.

01:32:24.291 --> 01:32:26.234
Wasn't Truman chairman
of that committee?

01:32:26.338 --> 01:32:30.276
Yeah, right. Now he's vice president.
Look what he did with it.

01:32:30.380 --> 01:32:33.180
No, I think...

01:32:33.305 --> 01:32:35.781
I think chairman.

01:32:35.885 --> 01:32:39.244
What do you think?

01:32:39.348 --> 01:32:42.123
- Chairman. That is interesting.
- Yeah.

01:32:42.227 --> 01:32:45.712
Let me show you these specs
for the DC-4.

01:32:45.816 --> 01:32:49.548
Ava, what do you think about
"Trans World Airlines"?

01:32:49.652 --> 01:32:52.131
"Transcontinental and Western"
just doesn't fit any more.

01:32:52.235 --> 01:32:55.011
Now that we're international,
we need a name that reflects that.

01:32:55.115 --> 01:32:57.972
"Trans World" is good.
Kind of peppy.

01:32:58.076 --> 01:33:00.276
TWA. Right?

01:33:00.744 --> 01:33:03.690
Keep the same initials. That way you
don't need to repaint any of the planes.

01:33:03.795 --> 01:33:06.980
That's you, always pinching pennies.

01:33:07.084 --> 01:33:09.155
Hand me my wrap.

01:33:23.137 --> 01:33:25.426
Knock it off.

01:33:31.520 --> 01:33:35.095
I have something for you.

01:33:35.199 --> 01:33:37.199
Stay here.

01:33:42.531 --> 01:33:45.311
- What the hell is this?
- It's a present.

01:33:45.415 --> 01:33:48.523
Go on and open it.

01:33:48.627 --> 01:33:52.028
A box of trash.
You shouldn't have.

01:33:52.133 --> 01:33:54.698
Keep looking.
Keep looking.

01:33:58.672 --> 01:34:01.664
It's a Kashmiri sapphire.
Best in the world.

01:34:01.768 --> 01:34:04.123
I had my boys all over the damn globe
looking for this.

01:34:04.227 --> 01:34:06.999
- Why?
- Because.

01:34:07.104 --> 01:34:10.960
Look.
It matches your eyes.

01:34:11.064 --> 01:34:13.546
I am not for sale.

01:34:13.650 --> 01:34:15.760
For Christ sakes, Ava,
it's just a present.

01:34:15.865 --> 01:34:19.219
You can't buy me, Howard,
so stop trying.

01:34:19.323 --> 01:34:22.848
Don't buy me any more diamonds or
sapphires or any other goddamn thing.

01:34:22.952 --> 01:34:26.144
You can buy me dinner.
How about that?

01:34:26.248 --> 01:34:27.570
Jesus, Ava.

01:34:28.410 --> 01:34:31.607
It's bad enough I have to endure
those filthy gym shoes of yours,

01:34:31.712 --> 01:34:36.695
but then I get all dolled up and we have
to go out in this old jalopy without a hood.

01:34:36.799 --> 01:34:39.991
Ava, will you marry me?

01:34:40.095 --> 01:34:41.410
No, Howard.

01:34:41.514 --> 01:34:45.625
- Why not, for heaven's sake?
- In the first place, I don't love you.

01:34:45.729 --> 01:34:48.167
In the second place, I'm still married.

01:34:48.271 --> 01:34:53.048
Look, you got girls stashed all over town.
You got a damn harem just at the Bel-Air.

01:34:53.152 --> 01:34:55.104
Why don't you marry
one of your bungalow girls?

01:34:55.229 --> 01:34:57.512
Those are employees.
I'm not going to marry an employee.

01:34:57.617 --> 01:35:00.519
Jesus Christ, how would that look?

01:35:06.115 --> 01:35:08.606
Good Lord, what is going on?

01:35:11.829 --> 01:35:14.534
- Oh, my God.
- Goddamn it.

01:35:16.041 --> 01:35:17.241
Faith.

01:35:18.093 --> 01:35:20.155
- Faith. What the hell?
- Look out.

01:35:20.259 --> 01:35:23.208
Goddamn, what the hell are you doing?

01:35:26.051 --> 01:35:28.915
- You OK, lady?
- What are you doing with her?

01:35:29.019 --> 01:35:31.754
We're going to dinner, that's all.
Now get out of there.

01:35:31.858 --> 01:35:33.919
Get that crazy bitch away from me.

01:35:34.023 --> 01:35:37.425
- Don't you love me any more?
- Course I love you, pork chop.

01:35:37.530 --> 01:35:39.758
- Ava, look over here.
- Howard.

01:35:39.862 --> 01:35:42.099
- Hey.
- Come on, Howard.

01:35:45.446 --> 01:35:47.750
Juan Trippe is working with
that goddamn Senator Brewster now.

01:35:47.854 --> 01:35:48.682
They're after you, Howard.

01:35:48.787 --> 01:35:51.940
If the Community Airline Bill becomes law,
we are finished, my friend.

01:35:52.044 --> 01:35:54.340
Pan Am will have a legal monopoly
on international travel.

01:35:54.444 --> 01:35:56.816
How can they justify it, Jack?
It's un-American.

01:35:56.920 --> 01:35:59.262
Senator Brewster's saying that
nationalised foreign carriers,

01:35:59.366 --> 01:36:00.738
like Air France and Lufthansa,

01:36:00.842 --> 01:36:03.700
can offer lower rates
cos they don't have to compete, right?

01:36:03.804 --> 01:36:05.977
So, hey, let's just get rid of
all that messy competition

01:36:06.081 --> 01:36:08.959
and have a nationalised airline of our own,
and why don't we make it Pan Am?

01:36:09.063 --> 01:36:10.836
I'm not kowtowing to Washington
or anyone else.

01:36:10.940 --> 01:36:12.916
- Howard, I need you up here.
- One sec, Odie.

01:36:13.020 --> 01:36:15.795
Look, we are Trans World Airlines,
all right?

01:36:15.899 --> 01:36:20.465
Get me something with a circle or a globe
or something round, for God's sake.

01:36:20.570 --> 01:36:23.306
Speak up. I know.
I don't give a rat's ass what he says.

01:36:23.410 --> 01:36:26.309
I'm not making a single cut.
Tell him I'm releasing without a seal.

01:36:26.413 --> 01:36:28.141
All right.
We gotta go public with this.

01:36:28.245 --> 01:36:30.251
I'm gonna talk to Hearst,
see what press he can give me,

01:36:30.355 --> 01:36:32.336
but sooner or later it's gonna come down
to a vote in the Senate,

01:36:32.441 --> 01:36:33.567
so we gotta get senators on our side.

01:36:33.671 --> 01:36:36.278
- What do you want me to do?
- Do what Trippe does, for Christ sake.

01:36:36.382 --> 01:36:37.650
Set up some offshore operations.

01:36:37.754 --> 01:36:40.011
See who's up for re-election.
Let's start making donations.

01:36:40.115 --> 01:36:43.491
- So, you want me to bribe senators?
- I don't want them bribed, Jack.

01:36:43.596 --> 01:36:46.201
I want it done legally.
I want them bought.

01:36:46.306 --> 01:36:48.227
And put a team of investigators
on Senator Brewster.

01:36:48.332 --> 01:36:50.833
I need to know everything there is to know
about that shit bag.

01:36:50.937 --> 01:36:53.920
Where he goes, what he says
and who he screws.

01:36:54.024 --> 01:36:57.218
- Get into it right now, Jack.
- You got it.

01:37:03.732 --> 01:37:06.484
Just give me a second.

01:37:07.403 --> 01:37:11.016
- All right. What do you need?
- Rudder and elevators.

01:37:11.120 --> 01:37:15.937
These are fine. Have Simon and Pete get
back to me on the hydraulic assemblies.

01:37:16.042 --> 01:37:19.815
- We need a secondary system here.
- OK.

01:37:19.919 --> 01:37:22.779
And listen, we need to take
another look at the wheel.

01:37:22.883 --> 01:37:27.367
- Jesus. The damn wheel?
- Yeah. It just doesn't feel right.

01:37:27.471 --> 01:37:31.666
Christ almighty, you've seen 8,000
goddamn wheels. Choose one, please.

01:37:31.770 --> 01:37:33.498
- Just one of them.
- I know. I know.

01:37:33.602 --> 01:37:35.998
- This one?
- I know. This one...

01:37:36.102 --> 01:37:38.213
This one's pretty close.

01:37:38.317 --> 01:37:40.385
Pretty close.

01:38:15.971 --> 01:38:16.971
Odie?

01:38:18.312 --> 01:38:21.005
That man sweeping up over there.

01:38:21.109 --> 01:38:24.259
Does he work for me?
I mean, have you seen him before?

01:38:24.363 --> 01:38:27.106
Name's Nick.
Something like that.

01:38:29.151 --> 01:38:31.025
Why's he looking at me?

01:38:33.155 --> 01:38:35.231
I don't know.

01:38:36.492 --> 01:38:39.899
Fire him. And make sure they use
damp brooms from now on.

01:38:40.004 --> 01:38:43.403
Respiratory diseases are expensive, and
I don't want a bunch of damn lawsuits.

01:38:43.507 --> 01:38:46.366
OK. But can we at least proceed
with the instrument panel we discussed?

01:38:46.471 --> 01:38:47.534
The tool shop's ready to go.

01:38:47.638 --> 01:38:49.557
- No. I wanna see the blueprints again.
- Howard,

01:38:49.661 --> 01:38:52.161
the deadline is now completely unrealistic.

01:38:52.265 --> 01:38:54.955
At this rate, the war is gonna be over
by the time she's done.

01:38:55.059 --> 01:38:57.499
Now, I need you here
to help consult on vital decisions

01:38:57.604 --> 01:38:59.295
and you're off dealing with movies.

01:38:59.399 --> 01:39:02.487
You got a thousand goddamn workers
waiting for you to make a decision here...

01:39:02.591 --> 01:39:04.175
Hey. Odie.

01:39:04.279 --> 01:39:07.761
Take it easy, all right?
I understand you're under a lot of pressure,

01:39:07.865 --> 01:39:13.095
but it's gonna do me no good if you
crack up on me like that. All right? Look.

01:39:13.199 --> 01:39:15.515
Take a couple of hours off, all right?

01:39:15.620 --> 01:39:17.562
- You relax a little.
- OK.

01:39:17.666 --> 01:39:20.272
- See your wife.
- OK.

01:39:20.376 --> 01:39:22.376
All right.

01:39:22.627 --> 01:39:26.405
- Be sure to show me all the blueprints.
- All right.

01:39:27.460 --> 01:39:29.951
Show me all the blueprints.

01:39:30.171 --> 01:39:32.240
Show me all the blueprints.

01:39:32.345 --> 01:39:37.411
I'm serious, now.
Show me all the blueprints.

01:39:37.515 --> 01:39:39.524
Show me all the blue...
Show me all the blueprints.

01:39:39.628 --> 01:39:42.293
- Howard...
- Show me all the blueprints.

01:39:42.397 --> 01:39:44.550
Show me all the blueprints.
Show me all the blueprints.

01:39:44.654 --> 01:39:48.425
Show me all the blueprints.
Show me all the blueprints.

01:39:48.530 --> 01:39:51.264
I want to get this done right,
so show me all the blueprints.

01:39:51.368 --> 01:39:52.929
Show me all the blueprints.

01:39:53.033 --> 01:39:55.060
Show me all the blueprints.
Show me all the blueprints.

01:39:55.164 --> 01:39:57.563
Show me all the blueprints.
Show me all the blueprints.

01:39:57.667 --> 01:40:00.059
- Show me all the blueprints.
- Howard.

01:40:00.163 --> 01:40:03.575
Show me all the blueprints.

01:40:03.788 --> 01:40:07.737
Show me all the blueprints.

01:40:07.958 --> 01:40:11.078
Show me all the blueprints.

01:40:32.233 --> 01:40:34.433
Quarantine.

01:40:35.328 --> 01:40:36.128
Q...

01:40:37.410 --> 01:40:38.210
U...

01:40:39.662 --> 01:40:40.462
A...

