02:12:34.490 --> 02:12:39.475
We both know I'm not gonna sell TWA.
Besides, you couldn't afford her anyway.

02:12:39.580 --> 02:12:43.942
Our domestic routes alone
are worth more than twice Pan Am.

02:12:44.047 --> 02:12:47.112
Well, considering our stock
is trading at three times yours,

02:12:47.217 --> 02:12:50.448
I find that a dubious claim, Howard.

02:12:50.552 --> 02:12:52.352
What I...

02:12:54.172 --> 02:12:58.790
What I mean is,
you have no domestic routes. All right?

02:12:58.894 --> 02:13:01.122
I mean, you get TWA,
you span the globe.

02:13:01.226 --> 02:13:04.213
Now, I'm not gonna sell,
and you know I'm not gonna sell.

02:13:04.317 --> 02:13:08.601
Here's the point.
Owen Brewster works for you.

02:13:09.229 --> 02:13:15.481
Howard, I didn't elect Senator Brewster.
We can thank the voters of Maine for that.

02:13:22.534 --> 02:13:28.112
Now, if I appear at his hearings, Juan,
it could get nasty.

02:13:28.216 --> 02:13:30.443
Real nasty for all of us.

02:13:30.547 --> 02:13:35.114
Well, I think considerably more so for you.

02:13:35.219 --> 02:13:38.244
While the good people of America
were losing sons at Anzio,

02:13:38.348 --> 02:13:42.414
you produced a dirty movie
and built airplanes that don't fly.

02:13:42.519 --> 02:13:45.082
Well, that's just not fair, is it?

02:13:45.186 --> 02:13:49.172
I mean, the XF-11 flew quite well
for an hour and 45 minutes.

02:13:49.277 --> 02:13:54.219
I mean, I wish you were up there with me,
Juan. It was exhilarating.

02:13:54.323 --> 02:13:58.434
Be that as it may, you still have
to answer for the Spruce Goose.

02:13:58.538 --> 02:14:01.059
It's called the Hercules.

02:14:01.163 --> 02:14:05.018
- And it will fly, goddamn it.
- I certainly hope so.

02:14:05.123 --> 02:14:08.693
The American people deserve something
for their $13 million.

02:14:08.797 --> 02:14:11.902
I won't sell TWA.

02:14:12.007 --> 02:14:13.245
I won't.

02:14:18.090 --> 02:14:20.831
I know that, Howard.

02:14:20.935 --> 02:14:23.002
I know that.

02:14:24.388 --> 02:14:27.879
But I'm going to get it anyway.

02:14:27.983 --> 02:14:30.377
You're going to default on
your loan from Equitable

02:14:30.481 --> 02:14:32.758
after Senator Brewster
destroys your reputation

02:14:32.862 --> 02:14:36.262
and you can't find additional capital
for the airline.

02:14:36.366 --> 02:14:39.849
The hearings will also show
Hughes Aircraft to be mismanaged

02:14:39.953 --> 02:14:44.063
and incompetent,
and it will go bankrupt, too.

02:14:44.167 --> 02:14:47.732
But you won't be insolvent.
You'll still have Toolco.

02:14:47.836 --> 02:14:51.862
Perhaps you'll head back to Houston
to rebuild your empire.

02:14:51.966 --> 02:14:54.404
I rather hope you do.

02:14:54.508 --> 02:14:57.115
By that time,
Pan Am will have bought TWA

02:14:57.219 --> 02:15:02.035
and painted all those
magnificent Connies blue and white.

02:15:02.139 --> 02:15:07.128
So when you do return,
it will be on a Pan Am plane.

02:15:10.601 --> 02:15:12.001
Well...

02:15:14.187 --> 02:15:18.011
You seem to have me
in a corner here, buddy.

02:15:18.115 --> 02:15:22.236
Not a position in which
I'm very comfortable.

02:15:23.113 --> 02:15:27.980
I think you're gonna be less comfortable
at Senator Brewster's hearings.

02:15:28.085 --> 02:15:31.695
Very public, Howard.

02:15:32.456 --> 02:15:35.863
Lots of cameras and newsmen.

02:15:35.968 --> 02:15:40.538
I understand you're not
particularly fond of crowds.

02:15:41.590 --> 02:15:44.793
Perhaps we should spare you that.

02:15:46.762 --> 02:15:51.668
Well, thank you for your concern, Juan.

02:15:51.772 --> 02:15:53.972
I find that

02:15:54.946 --> 02:15:57.346
very moving.

02:15:57.821 --> 02:16:00.056
It's been a real pleasure.

02:16:01.568 --> 02:16:05.514
Noah will see you back to the airport.
Now you...

02:16:05.618 --> 02:16:07.192
You fly safe.

02:16:10.786 --> 02:16:13.193
You fly safe.

02:16:18.043 --> 02:16:20.097
Thank you, Howard.
And you take care of that cold.

02:16:20.201 --> 02:16:22.868
Don't you worry.

02:16:22.972 --> 02:16:26.078
I certainly will.

02:16:26.182 --> 02:16:27.782
Bye-bye.

02:16:32.432 --> 02:16:37.338
If you let him appear at those hearings,
the whole world will see what he's become.

02:16:37.442 --> 02:16:40.557
People should remember him as he was.

02:16:45.529 --> 02:16:50.146
He'll have a subpoena in three days
to appear in Washington.

02:16:50.250 --> 02:16:52.994
If you can get him out of there by then.

02:17:42.710 --> 02:17:44.668
Mr Hughes?

02:17:50.593 --> 02:17:53.084
I don't have any shoes.

02:17:54.848 --> 02:17:57.710
- Could you get me some shoes?
- Shoes.

02:17:57.816 --> 02:17:58.816
Yeah.

02:18:25.379 --> 02:18:28.083
How nice of you to dress for me.

02:18:31.218 --> 02:18:33.459
Can I come in?

02:18:34.012 --> 02:18:37.713
Yeah. Yeah.
You can come in.

02:18:45.398 --> 02:18:47.937
Thank you for coming.

02:18:59.745 --> 02:19:01.900
Now, let's get a drink.

02:19:02.004 --> 02:19:04.990
Wait, wait, wait, honey.
You can't move. You can't move.

02:19:05.093 --> 02:19:09.492
You're safe here. You're in the germ-free
zone now. You understand?

02:19:09.596 --> 02:19:13.285
- I'll take my chances.
- Oh, no. No, no, honey.

02:19:13.388 --> 02:19:15.958
Wait, wait, wait.

02:19:28.150 --> 02:19:32.147
Love what you've done with the place.

02:19:37.367 --> 02:19:41.531
Now, let me look at you.

02:19:46.126 --> 02:19:49.034
When do you go to Washington?

02:19:49.138 --> 02:19:50.538
A week.

02:19:51.136 --> 02:19:53.368
No, no.
Just under a week.

02:19:53.472 --> 02:19:58.834
I don't know the date today,
but I have to be... I have to be...

02:19:58.938 --> 02:20:01.386
All right, take it easy.

02:20:14.363 --> 02:20:17.150
There's nothing there, Howard.

02:20:19.034 --> 02:20:19.634
Mm.

02:20:23.872 --> 02:20:27.455
You know, I...
I see things.

02:20:28.293 --> 02:20:30.784
I know, baby.

02:20:31.380 --> 02:20:33.668
Rinse your face off now.

02:20:42.558 --> 02:20:45.088
Put your hands in the water
and wash off the soap.

02:20:45.192 --> 02:20:48.554
I'm right here.
I'm not going anywhere.

02:20:52.943 --> 02:20:56.389
- Does that look clean to you?
- Nothing's clean, Howard.

02:20:56.493 --> 02:20:59.608
But we do our best, right?

02:21:00.325 --> 02:21:01.325
Yeah.

02:21:21.305 --> 02:21:24.380
- What do you think?
- I look all right?

02:21:24.484 --> 02:21:26.672
You look great.

02:21:26.777 --> 02:21:30.469
- Will you marry me?
- You're too crazy for me.

02:21:32.941 --> 02:21:36.182
I gotta go, baby.

02:21:36.286 --> 02:21:36.886
OK.

02:21:38.663 --> 02:21:40.063
Thanks.

02:21:46.371 --> 02:21:48.945
You'd do it for me.

02:21:54.796 --> 02:21:57.085
Hi, Howard.
How are you doing?

02:22:37.714 --> 02:22:40.539
The Committee will come to order.

02:22:40.643 --> 02:22:45.501
Ladies and gentlemen, I must insist that we
maintain quiet during these proceedings.

02:22:45.606 --> 02:22:49.429
All right, Mr Hughes,
will you stand to be sworn?

02:22:50.727 --> 02:22:54.634
Do you solemnly swear that in the matter
now pending before this committee,

02:22:54.739 --> 02:22:59.016
you will tell the truth, the whole truth and
nothing but the truth, so help you God?

02:22:59.120 --> 02:23:01.513
- I do.
- Pardon me for speaking loudly,

02:23:01.617 --> 02:23:03.977
but I understand
you have some difficulty hearing.

02:23:04.081 --> 02:23:09.069
That's quite all right. Everybody knows
I'm deaf. I'm not gonna try to hide it.

02:23:12.249 --> 02:23:14.735
Mr Hughes,
it is the intention of this committee...

02:23:14.839 --> 02:23:17.782
Mr Hughes has a statement.

02:23:17.886 --> 02:23:23.965
All right. All right. You may proceed
with this statement, Mr Hughes.

02:23:30.100 --> 02:23:33.469
Mr Hughes, do you have a statement?

02:23:39.818 --> 02:23:44.195
I'm gonna attempt to be honest here.

02:23:44.865 --> 02:23:50.526
My reputation's being destroyed, so I might
as well lay the cards on the table.

02:23:50.630 --> 02:23:54.944
Senator Brewster,
if you hadn't have gone too far overboard,

02:23:55.048 --> 02:23:57.611
if you hadn't have put
the red-hot iron in my side,

02:23:57.715 --> 02:24:02.283
I might have been willing to take a
shellacking in this publicity spree of yours.

02:24:02.388 --> 02:24:05.745
I might have been willing to sit back
and take a certain amount of abuse.

02:24:05.849 --> 02:24:08.624
Simply because, well...

02:24:08.728 --> 02:24:11.381
Well, I am only a private citizen,

02:24:11.485 --> 02:24:16.350
whereas you are a senator,
with all sorts of powers.

02:24:17.522 --> 02:24:20.302
But I think this goddamn circus
has gone on long enough.

02:24:20.407 --> 02:24:21.721
That's quite sufficient.

02:24:21.826 --> 02:24:24.643
You have called me a liar, sir, in the press.

02:24:24.747 --> 02:24:27.730
You have called me a liar
and a thief and a war profiteer.

02:24:27.834 --> 02:24:31.942
- The witness will restrain his comments...
- Why not tell the truth for once, Senator?

02:24:32.046 --> 02:24:35.234
Why not tell the truth
that this investigation was really born

02:24:35.338 --> 02:24:38.362
on the day that TWA
first decided to fly to Europe?

02:24:38.466 --> 02:24:41.784
On the day that TWA
first invaded Juan Trippe's territory.

02:24:41.889 --> 02:24:43.245
Sit down, Mr Hughes.

02:24:43.349 --> 02:24:46.870
On the day that TWA first challenged
the generally accepted theory

02:24:46.974 --> 02:24:49.666
that only Juan Trippe's
great Pan American Airways

02:24:49.770 --> 02:24:55.002
- had the sacred right to fly the Atlantic.
- You are not here to make a speech.

02:24:55.106 --> 02:24:58.509
I asked for silence.
I asked for quiet in this room...

02:24:58.614 --> 02:25:03.428
We have in our possession receipts
in the amount of $170,000

02:25:03.532 --> 02:25:05.641
acquired from Mr John Meyer.

02:25:05.746 --> 02:25:08.223
Mr Meyer works for you,
does he not?

02:25:08.327 --> 02:25:13.273
- He does.
- And what is his official title?

02:25:13.377 --> 02:25:17.232
Well, I don't exactly know, Senator.
A lot of people work for me.

02:25:17.336 --> 02:25:22.782
Can you explain why your press agent
would pay out more than a $170,000

02:25:22.886 --> 02:25:25.327
to representatives of
the United States Air Force?

02:25:25.431 --> 02:25:28.204
I don't know.
I suppose you'd have to ask him, Senator.

02:25:28.308 --> 02:25:32.209
- Well, would you produce him?
- Produce him?

02:25:32.313 --> 02:25:34.459
- Will you cause him to appear?
- Well, Senator,

02:25:34.563 --> 02:25:37.421
you had John Meyer on
the stand for three days last week.

02:25:37.525 --> 02:25:43.937
Well, be that as it may, we would like him
to reappear. Would you ask him to return?

02:25:49.740 --> 02:25:53.602
No, I don't think I will.

02:25:53.706 --> 02:25:56.110
Will you try to have him return?

02:25:57.372 --> 02:26:01.029
Well, no, I don't think I'll try.

02:26:01.133 --> 02:26:03.582
You don't think you'll try?

02:26:04.546 --> 02:26:07.704
No, I don't think so.

02:26:07.808 --> 02:26:12.583
The $170,000 paid out to the Air Force
in the form of hotel suites,

02:26:12.688 --> 02:26:14.688
TWA stock,

02:26:14.937 --> 02:26:17.590
female companionship...

02:26:17.695 --> 02:26:22.062
Now, is it possible
that these could be considered bribes?

02:26:22.564 --> 02:26:26.139
I suppose you could call them that, yes.

02:26:26.243 --> 02:26:28.515
Would you repeat that?

02:26:28.619 --> 02:26:32.610
I said, I suppose you could
consider them bribes, yes.

02:26:35.160 --> 02:26:38.690
Well, would you like
to explain that, Mr Hughes?

02:26:38.794 --> 02:26:43.944
Well, I'm afraid you don't know how
the aviation business works, Senator.

02:26:44.048 --> 02:26:48.661
See, wining and dining Air Force
dignitaries is common in our business.

02:26:48.765 --> 02:26:52.581
It's because we all want the big contracts.
All the major aircraft companies do it.

02:26:52.685 --> 02:26:57.046
Now, I don't know whether it's a good
system or not. I just know it's not illegal.

02:26:57.150 --> 02:27:00.337
You, Senator, you are the lawmaker.

02:27:00.442 --> 02:27:03.760
If you pass a law that states
no one can entertain Air Force officers,

02:27:03.864 --> 02:27:07.556
well, hell,
I'd be happy to abide by it.

02:27:09.486 --> 02:27:11.556
Senator Brewster,
your story is a pack of lies,

02:27:11.660 --> 02:27:14.186
and I can tear it apart
if allowed to cross-examine you.

02:27:14.290 --> 02:27:16.685
- We're not gonna have this bickering...
- Yes.

02:27:16.789 --> 02:27:19.402
Somewhere between two and five hundred,
if you'll just let me...

02:27:19.507 --> 02:27:22.234
Now, if you believe that
because of your great wealth and power,

02:27:22.339 --> 02:27:24.818
you can intimidate
any member of this committee,

02:27:24.922 --> 02:27:26.783
I want to advise you that you're mistaken.

02:27:26.887 --> 02:27:29.871
- Now, submit your questions to the chair.
- Now, I'll put this very simply.

02:27:29.975 --> 02:27:33.122
On February 12th at the Mayflower Hotel,

02:27:33.227 --> 02:27:38.879
did you, or did you not, tell me
that if I were to sell TWA to Pan Am

02:27:38.983 --> 02:27:41.799
that this entire investigation
would be called off?

02:27:41.903 --> 02:27:45.717
No, I did not. I have asked you repeatedly
to submit your questions in writing.

02:27:45.821 --> 02:27:49.471
- How long have you known Juan Trippe?
- I've known Mr Trippe for some time now,

02:27:49.575 --> 02:27:51.305
and that's not the question here.

02:27:51.409 --> 02:27:55.937
Is it not true that Juan Trippe donated
$ 20,000 to your last campaign?

02:27:56.041 --> 02:27:59.395
I mean, he spoke to me
as if you worked for him.

02:27:59.500 --> 02:28:01.154
All right.

02:28:03.123 --> 02:28:04.927
I have a personal friendship
with Mr Trippe...

02:28:05.031 --> 02:28:08.530
Is it true that you accept free tickets
from Pan Am so you can circle the globe

02:28:08.634 --> 02:28:11.704
- in support of your CAB bill?
- No, no, it is not true.

02:28:11.808 --> 02:28:16.083
Well, who wrote that bill, Senator?
Who actually wrote the CAB bill?

02:28:16.187 --> 02:28:18.376
The actual words in the bill,
did you write them?

02:28:18.480 --> 02:28:21.152
This is not how these hearings
are gonna be conducted, Mr Hughes.

02:28:21.256 --> 02:28:24.421
I have it right here.
Maybe it'll refresh your memory.

02:28:24.526 --> 02:28:27.844
"Bill S-987,
to amend the Civil Aeronautics Act."

02:28:27.948 --> 02:28:31.807
Now, you introduced
this bill to the Senate.

02:28:34.738 --> 02:28:37.102
Lot of words.

02:28:37.206 --> 02:28:39.563
You write all of them?

02:28:39.667 --> 02:28:42.606
- Did you write any of them, Senator?
- Now look, Mr Hughes.

02:28:42.711 --> 02:28:45.862
Now, this entire bill
was written by Pan Am executives

02:28:45.966 --> 02:28:50.159
and designed to give that airline
a monopoly on international travel.

02:28:50.263 --> 02:28:53.494
And you've been flogging this bill
all around the world on their behalf,

02:28:53.599 --> 02:28:54.867
have you not?

02:28:54.971 --> 02:28:58.874
I have duties that take me
all over the world, Mr Hughes.

02:28:58.978 --> 02:29:04.048
Well, what the hell does a senator
from Maine need to visit Peru for?

02:29:04.601 --> 02:29:08.886
I was seeking outlets
for our trade goods.

02:29:08.990 --> 02:29:12.480
Buy a lot of lobsters down there,
do they?

02:29:15.821 --> 02:29:19.184
Senator Brewster, how many times
have you visited Juan Trippe's office

02:29:19.288 --> 02:29:23.411
in New York in the last three months?

02:29:24.913 --> 02:29:27.700
Would you like me to tell you, Senator?

02:29:28.292 --> 02:29:31.738
All right, this has gone on long enough.
Juan Trippe is a great American.

02:29:31.842 --> 02:29:35.660
His airline has advanced the cause
of commercial aviation in this country

02:29:35.765 --> 02:29:38.038
for decades.
Juan Trippe is a patriot.

02:29:38.142 --> 02:29:41.468
Juan Trippe is not a man
who is interested in making money.

02:29:42.931 --> 02:29:46.134
Well, I'm sure his stockholders
will be happy to hear that.

02:29:48.312 --> 02:29:50.304
I'm telling you,
we're gonna clear this room.

02:29:51.398 --> 02:29:52.785
This is James McNamara
speaking to you

02:29:52.889 --> 02:29:57.097
from aboard the Howard Hughes 2000-ton
flying boat, the world's largest aircraft.

02:29:57.202 --> 02:29:59.765
This is the sky giant
which has prompted Congress

02:29:59.869 --> 02:30:02.562
to investigate
the war contracts of Mr Hughes.

02:30:02.667 --> 02:30:05.484
Today, before boarding the craft,
Mr Hughes told newsmen

02:30:05.588 --> 02:30:08.320
that this test would
be solely a taxi experiment.

02:30:08.424 --> 02:30:10.401
He said he didn't know
what might happen.

02:30:10.506 --> 02:30:13.159
He pointed out that the mammoth
flying plywood shell

02:30:13.264 --> 02:30:17.160
might ship some water under high-speed
taxi pressure. He said definitely, however,

02:30:17.265 --> 02:30:20.748
that he would not take the craft into the air
until next spring.

02:30:20.852 --> 02:30:24.917
The thin man from Culver City pronounced
the craft an unknown quantity.

02:30:25.021 --> 02:30:26.585
Hi, boys.

02:30:26.690 --> 02:30:28.446
All right, none of that, now.
None of that.

02:30:28.550 --> 02:30:31.798
As we speak to you, we're about
five feet in back of Mr Hughes,

02:30:31.902 --> 02:30:35.804
and we are looking through
one of the side windows in the cockpit.

02:30:35.908 --> 02:30:38.560
Professor, why don't you
come on up front here?

02:30:38.664 --> 02:30:42.228
In other words,
we are 30 feet high in this aircraft.

02:30:42.332 --> 02:30:45.212
Strap yourself in right there.
You ought to be able to see just great.

02:30:45.317 --> 02:30:47.899
...just how gigantic this ship is.

02:30:48.004 --> 02:30:51.237
Huge crowds jammed
the surrounding shoreline this morning...

02:30:51.341 --> 02:30:54.667
All right, boys.
Let's fire it up.

02:30:58.423 --> 02:31:00.623
One's good.

02:31:01.097 --> 02:31:03.163
Two's good.

02:31:03.267 --> 02:31:04.960
Three's good.

02:31:05.064 --> 02:31:07.208
Four's good.

02:31:07.312 --> 02:31:09.128
Five's good.

02:31:09.232 --> 02:31:10.758
Six is good.

02:31:10.862 --> 02:31:12.301
Seven's good.

02:31:12.405 --> 02:31:15.005
Eight's good.

02:31:15.159 --> 02:31:20.681
- Advancing master throttles.
- Advancing master throttles.

02:31:20.785 --> 02:31:21.936
As you probably know by now,

02:31:22.041 --> 02:31:24.689
I have to do a great deal of screaming
here into my microphone.

02:31:24.794 --> 02:31:26.853
- Prop start up.
- Understood.

02:31:26.957 --> 02:31:30.942
- Lowering 15 degrees of flaps.
- Lowering 15 degrees of flaps.

02:31:31.047 --> 02:31:32.404
Howard.

02:31:32.509 --> 02:31:34.863
She's gotta hit 70
to have any kind of chance.

02:31:34.967 --> 02:31:36.742
Yeah, I know. I know.

02:31:36.846 --> 02:31:40.616
I might add that it's a beautiful day over
here off the coast of Southern California.

02:31:40.720 --> 02:31:43.246
Crystal blue skies, a warm sun...

02:31:43.351 --> 02:31:46.130
25 miles per hour.

02:31:47.264 --> 02:31:47.864
30.

02:31:49.521 --> 02:31:50.121
35.

02:31:50.897 --> 02:31:54.883
One would think these eight power plants
might shake the mighty craft to pieces.

02:31:54.987 --> 02:31:56.844
Take it easy, Howard.

02:31:56.949 --> 02:31:59.010
...and certainly, it's holding up...

02:31:59.114 --> 02:32:03.016
- 40.
- Throttling back for starboard turn 180.

02:32:03.120 --> 02:32:06.862
Throttling back for starboard turn 180.

02:32:10.495 --> 02:32:13.275
The flight crew itself consists of four men.

02:32:13.380 --> 02:32:17.446
Mr Hughes, however, has added 11
maintenance men to this maiden taxi test,

02:32:17.550 --> 02:32:20.075
stationed at various places
throughout the ship,

02:32:20.179 --> 02:32:23.541
checking points of stress and strain.

02:32:25.594 --> 02:32:28.080
How does she sound, Odie?

02:32:28.184 --> 02:32:30.256
Sounds good, Howard.

02:32:33.352 --> 02:32:35.632
- Professor.
- Yes?

02:32:35.736 --> 02:32:38.009
Would you do me a favour?

02:32:38.114 --> 02:32:44.358
Would you take a look out that window
there and tell me what the wind is doing?

02:32:47.241 --> 02:32:51.148
I would say that we have
a 15-knot wind.

02:32:51.252 --> 02:32:55.242
Would you call that a headwind,
Professor?

02:32:55.832 --> 02:32:57.319
I would, Mr Hughes.

02:32:57.424 --> 02:32:59.737
I must insist that we maintain silence.

02:32:59.842 --> 02:33:01.823
We must have quiet during
these proceedings.

02:33:01.927 --> 02:33:04.369
All right, Mr Hughes,
will you stand to be sworn?

02:33:04.473 --> 02:33:08.245
Mr Hughes,
did you receive $43 million

02:33:08.349 --> 02:33:14.627
to manufacture one hundred XF-11
spy planes for the United States Air Force?

02:33:14.732 --> 02:33:15.919
I did.

02:33:16.023 --> 02:33:20.387
How many functional planes did you
deliver to the United States Air Force?

02:33:20.492 --> 02:33:21.492
None.

02:33:21.824 --> 02:33:25.474
Would you lean a little closer
to the microphone, sir?

02:33:25.578 --> 02:33:26.578
None.

02:33:26.913 --> 02:33:30.812
Did you receive $13 million to manufacture

02:33:30.917 --> 02:33:35.867
a prototype of a flying boat
known as the Hercules?

02:33:36.456 --> 02:33:37.656
I did.

02:33:38.759 --> 02:33:41.659
And did you deliver that plane?

02:33:41.763 --> 02:33:43.763
I did not.

02:33:44.011 --> 02:33:47.497
So, by your admission in this chamber,
Mr Hughes,

02:33:47.601 --> 02:33:52.793
you have received $56 million
from the United States government

02:33:52.897 --> 02:33:55.753
for planes you never delivered.

02:33:55.857 --> 02:33:58.721
That is correct.

02:33:59.980 --> 02:34:05.219
Well, excuse me for asking, Mr Hughes,
but where did all that money go?

02:34:05.323 --> 02:34:10.141
Well, it went into the plane, Senator,
and a lot more.

02:34:10.245 --> 02:34:15.146
More? Do tell, Mr Hughes.
What other larcenies did you commit?

02:34:15.250 --> 02:34:20.666
I mean, I put my money
into the plane, Senator. My money.

02:34:23.003 --> 02:34:24.824
- See, the thing is...
- Mr Hughes,

02:34:24.928 --> 02:34:27.701
your personal finances are not...

02:34:27.806 --> 02:34:30.551
Let him speak.

02:34:33.764 --> 02:34:37.088
All right, proceed, Mr Hughes.

02:34:37.192 --> 02:34:42.678
See, the thing is,
I care very much about aviation.

02:34:42.782 --> 02:34:46.635
It has been the great joy of my life. That's
why I put my own money into these planes.

02:34:46.739 --> 02:34:49.137
And I have lost millions, Senator Brewster.

02:34:49.242 --> 02:34:54.309
And I'll go on losing millions.
It's just what I do.

02:34:54.414 --> 02:34:58.188
Now, if I've lost a lot of the government's
money during the war,

02:34:58.292 --> 02:35:01.612
well, I hope folks
will put that into perspective.

02:35:01.717 --> 02:35:03.778
You see, more than 60 other airplanes,

02:35:03.882 --> 02:35:07.157
ordered from such firms as Lockheed,
Douglas, Northrop and Boeing,

02:35:07.261 --> 02:35:09.287
never saw action, either.

02:35:09.391 --> 02:35:15.998
In all, more than $800 million was spent
during the war on planes that never flew.

02:35:16.102 --> 02:35:20.466
Over six billion on other weapons
that were never delivered.

02:35:20.570 --> 02:35:25.844
Yet Hughes Aircraft, with her 56 million,

02:35:25.948 --> 02:35:28.600
is the only firm
under investigation here today.

02:35:28.704 --> 02:35:31.851
Now, I cannot help but think
that has a little more to do with TWA

02:35:31.955 --> 02:35:33.850
than planes that did not fly.

02:35:33.954 --> 02:35:36.857
- I think you've made your point...
- One second.

02:35:36.961 --> 02:35:41.070
Senator Brewster, I have one more thing
to say here to this committee,

02:35:41.174 --> 02:35:44.278
and that has to do with the Hercules.

02:35:44.382 --> 02:35:49.704
Now, I am supposed to be many things
which are not complimentary.

02:35:49.809 --> 02:35:51.951
I am supposed to be capricious.

02:35:52.056 --> 02:35:56.168
I have been called a playboy.
I've even been called an eccentric.

02:35:56.272 --> 02:36:01.213
But I do not believe that I have
the reputation of being a liar.

02:36:01.317 --> 02:36:04.884
Now, needless to say, the Hercules
was a monumental undertaking.

02:36:04.988 --> 02:36:07.721
It is the largest plane ever built.

02:36:07.826 --> 02:36:11.473
It's over five storeys tall,
with a wingspan longer than a football field.

02:36:11.577 --> 02:36:13.684
That's more than a city block.

02:36:13.789 --> 02:36:18.270
Now, I put the sweat of my life into this
thing, I got my reputation all rolled up in it,

02:36:18.375 --> 02:36:21.776
and I have stated several times
that if the Hercules fails to fly

02:36:21.880 --> 02:36:24.697
I will leave this country
and never come back.

02:36:24.801 --> 02:36:27.533
And I mean it.

02:36:27.637 --> 02:36:32.617
Now, Senator Brewster,
you can subpoena me. You can arrest me.

02:36:32.721 --> 02:36:37.955
You can even claim that I've folded up
and taken a run-out powder, but, well...

02:36:38.059 --> 02:36:41.711
I've had just about enough
of this nonsense. Good afternoon.

02:36:41.816 --> 02:36:43.424
I had to do it.

02:36:43.528 --> 02:36:46.638
Mr Hughes. Mr Hughes.

02:36:47.606 --> 02:36:50.303
I'd love to see the Hercules in the air.

02:36:50.408 --> 02:36:52.773
Thank you.
Thank you so much.

02:36:54.696 --> 02:36:57.816
Excuse us.
Excuse us, please. Thank you.

02:36:58.992 --> 02:37:01.281
Thank you, thank you, thank you.

02:37:01.828 --> 02:37:03.830
- Switch it off.
- The hearings aren't over yet.

02:37:03.956 --> 02:37:05.948
The hearings are over.

02:37:08.669 --> 02:37:11.577
The airline bill
will be defeated in the Senate.

02:37:11.681 --> 02:37:14.785
TWA will begin flights
from New York to Paris.

02:37:14.889 --> 02:37:19.675
Then on to Moscow, to Japan,
